<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Finance &amp; The Family (Briefcase): Demand on arrears
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING abolition of the 'earnings rule', my wife applied for state
retirement pension in May 1990 backdated to October 2, 1989.
The application was accepted and the first payment made at the end of June
1990, including arrears from October 2, 1989.
The Inland Revenue demanded payment of tax on the arrears assessing them as
1989/90 income, notwithstanding the fact that the pension was only applied
for, and paid during the 1990/91 income tax year. Is this treatment correct?
Yes, under section 41(2) of the Finance Act 1989: 'As regards any particular
year of assessment, income tax shall be charged on the amount of the pension
or other benefit accruing in respect of the year; and this shall apply
irrespective of when any amount is actually paid in respect of the pension
or other benefit.'
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
