<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / The Long View: Shares that defy the gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER YOU may think about the poor old British economy, the UK stock
market has been a distinctly more sprightly animal. In 1990 it has more or
less kept pace with the other major world markets despite the particular
intensity of the local recession. Its ability to generate high returns over
the years has been a indication that, in some respects at least, the British
corporate sector has performed quite strongly.
There is a reminder here from the new 1991 edition of Phillips &amp; Drew Fund
Managers' Pension Fund Indicators, which records that the average gross
annual return of 18.9 per cent on UK equities (dividend income plus capital
gains) during the ten years 1981-90 compares with 16.7 per cent on overseas
equities. A gap of little more than 2 percentage points may not sound much,
but it compounds to 25 per cent over a decade.
A rather more elaborate study of the long-term returns from four different
national stock markets has been produced by Paul Bostock and Paul Woolley of
the London investment boutique GMO Woolley. Published in the US Financial
Analysts Journal, it shows that in terms of fundamental value delivered to
investors British listed companies have indeed outperformed their rivals in
the US, Japan and Germany over any five-year or ten-year period within the
past twenty years. But currency and market valuation effects have sometimes
predominated, most notably in the Tokyo market.
Different local inflation rates, and volatile exchange rates, naturally make
it difficult to compare stock market returns. Bostock and Woolley have
broken down the overall returns into what they call a value-based measure,
taking in dividend income and real (inflation-adjusted) earnings growth,
together with two revaluation effects. The currency revaluation factor
(usually quite small over a long period) reflects exchange rate movements
over and above those required to maintain purchasing power parities; and the
market revaluation factor (sometimes quite large) reflects changes in the
market's average price-earnings ratio, an effect most dramatically seen in
Tokyo during the late 1980s when it was adding about 14 per cent each year
to the returns enjoyed by investors (though storing up a certain amount of
trouble for 1990, when Toyko crashed).
During the 20 years 1970-89 the UK delivered 7.8 per cent a year in terms of
combined income and real earnings growth, against about 5 per cent in each
of the other three markets. But the market revaluation effect pushed Japan
well ahead, to give an overall annual return of 22.8 per cent in dollars.
Even so, the UK return of 13.9 per cent was well ahead of the US figure of
10.6 per cent, and almost up with the 14.2 per cent return from German
equities.
Over the five years 1985-89 the UK again came top of the value measures,
largely because of the relatively high income (4.5 per cent compared with,
at the other extreme, 0.6 per cent in Japan). However, particularly powerful
revaluation factors sent both Japan and Germany well ahead on total return.
Still, London's return of 28.8 per cent at least trounced the 19.7 per cent
from Wall Street.
There are several curious features about all this. For example, there
appears to be no very close correlation between national economic growth and
corporate performance. True, Japan has consistently produced the fastest
economic growth and the best earnings growth (though not superior enough to
compensate for the meagre dividends). However, German corporate earnings
growth has been poor despite a generally good economic growth record, and
earnings growth has been worst of all in the US, even though its real annual
GDP growth rate has been a respectable 2.8 per cent over 20 years (against
2.5 per cent for the UK).
Secondly, the market revaluation effects have been inconsistent. You would
expect that investors would place a higher value on faster-growing earnings.
That indeed has happened in Japan, but it has also happened in recent years
in the US, where earnings growth has been particularly poor by international
standards. As for the UK, the much more buoyant corporate performance here
has been greeted by little or no price-earnings multiple expansion at all.
Is there no justice?
In the case of British companies they may indeed have been getting their
just deserts, because the quality of earnings has been deteriorating,
especially during the 1980s, because of lax accounting practices.
International investors have clearly become suspicious of the bottom line
obsessions of British managements. When UK company accounts are converted to
US standards, earnings typically take a dive.
The relationship of stock market performance to national growth is complex.
In Germany the narrowly-based stock market is unrepresentative of the
multitude of medium-sized, private companies which have made up the
economy's powerhouse. There is a much broader spread of listings in Japan,
but shareholders tend to come a long way down corporate priority lists:
hence the meagre dividend payments.
Anyway, the domicile of a company does not necessarily reflect with any
precision the geographical location of its activities. British listed
companies earn some 40 per cent of their profits from overseas subsidiaries,
and another 10 per cent or so from exports. If you extrapolate this process
to its limit, a country's framework of tax, law and markets may eventually
become more important to large companies than its economic success.
The case of the US is probably the oddest of all. Many of its major
companies have performed poorly over many years, and yet recently the
price-earnings multiples on Wall Street have expanded to levels which have
begun to frighten quite a few professional investors. It could be that the
market is saying something about the potential for corporate earnings
recovery after the recession, or just that investors are vainly seeking to
rediscover in stocks the value that has disappeared from the US bond market.
Maybe every dog has its day, but some should be kept on a short lead.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
