<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / DM1bn project to clean up east German industrial area
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A PIONEERING agreement was announced in Germany yesterday between
government, industry and the Treuhand privatisation agency to clean up and
modernise one of the largest and most polluted industrial areas in east
Germany.
The operation, which could eventually cost at least DM1bn (Pounds 338m),
will focus on the region surrounding the Mansfeld metal conglomerate, near
Halle. It involves a partnership between Metallgesellschaft, the
Frankfurt-based metals, mining and engineering company, and US and European
concerns, and could provide a model for rehabilitation of other polluted
parts of Germany.
Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch, Metallgesellschaft's chief executive, said: 'The
programme should act as a signal for other such operations to be carried out
elsewhere in east Germany.' He has negotiated the agreement over the past
year with the Treuhand, owner of the Mansfeld concern, the government of the
state of Saxony-Anhalt, where it is based, and other German and
international companies.
Mansfeld, which mainly produces copper and aluminium, was one of east
Germany's biggest kombinats (industrial groups), employing 48,000. It now
has around 30,000 workers and its survival is in doubt because of heavy cost
and pollution problems.
For Metallgesellschaft and its partners, however, it would provide a
ready-made site for expansion at a time when approval of new sites in west
Germany can take years.
The agreement reached this week in Magdeburg, the state's capital, provides
for Metallgesellschaft to head a consortium to produce a feasibility study
for rehabilitation of the Mansfeld area. The next stages, once the study is
finished, involve cleaning the soil, modernising the smelters, installing a
new power plant and attracting new industry.
Metallgesellschaft has much experience of business in east Germany and
eastern Europe, including the Soviet Union. Its Lurgi engineering subsidiary
has developed soil decontamination technology which would be used in
Mansfeld.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
