<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Shares drift ahead of long weekend
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON SHARES drifted lower in quiet trading as investors and marketmakers
avoided risks ahead of the holiday weekend.
The mood was subdued as the market acknowledged that the local elections
results were discomforting for the Conservative Party.
A modest overnight rise in New York inspired no one. On the opening of the
new session, Wall Street lost ground as US employment figures indicated
there was little pressure for the Federal Reserve to cut interest rates
further in the short term.
UK equity strategists varied from the cautious to the pessimistic. Mr John
Reynolds County NatWest argued that since the swing away from the
Conservatives was only partly towards the opposition Labour Party, the
disappointment of the results was cushioned. He pointed to a limited fall in
the share prices and sterling's resilience as evidence: 'there is scope for
one per cent off interest rates over the next few months,' he said. A half
percentage point is already discounted in the money markets.
Mr Ian Harnett at Strauss Turnbull had a different interpretation of the
polls. He said that the results had been 'the worst possible' for the
market. Support for the centrist Liberal Democrats raised the prospect of a
hung parliament and associated uncertainties.
He also thought that the Conservative government would have to wait until
1992 before calling an election - unemployment would be rising too quickly
in the autumn. There were dangers, too, of political interest rates cuts
that would reap only small electoral benefits.
Mr Harnett added that the danger period for shares was the next few days of
trading. If the market survived next week at current levels it could then
rise quickly. Chartists elsewhere agreed, saying that although the
fundamentals were negative, the market was 'behaving as if it had upside
potential'.
Faced with such diversity, investors did little. The Footsie index spent the
entire day just inside negative territory. There was little trade to
persuade marketmakers to change their prices and the index moved in a narrow
range before ending 1.9 above the day's low at 2522.7. The net fall was 8
and turnover an unspectacular 452.7m shares.
The dollar's late recovery, gaining more than two cents against sterling,
helped international stocks. Wellcome again the among the best performers as
upbeat press and analysts' comment followed the Thursda's results.
Gilts opened a little easier on worries that sterling could weaken after the
polls. They soon rallied only to lose ground when US bonds fell on the US
employment figures. Gilts ended up to  1/4 point off.
Caution ahead of local polls meant low volume. Bid talk helped levels on
Thursday, but funds were disinclined to commit much cash ahead of next set
of inflation data.
</TEXT>
