<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Foreign Exchanges: Employment data boost dollar
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOLLAR rose yesterday on news of stronger than expected April US
employment data. A surprising fall to 6.6 from 6.8 per cent in the
unemployment rate and a smaller than forecast fall of 124,000 in non-farm
payrolls, against a revised drop of 241,000 in March, led to demand for the
US currency.
Analysts were looking for a rise to 7.0 per cent in the unemployment rate
and for a fall of about 170,000 in the payrolls figure. The better data were
regarded as possibly the first concrete sign that the US economy is moving
out of recession.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, a White House spokesman, said it was welcome news, but
he was cautious whether the figures signalled an end to the recession. A
commissioner for the US Bureau of Labor Statistics warned that the
unemployment rate probably exaggerated the improvement.
This caution in official circles pulled the dollar back from peaks of
DM1.7540 and Y138.90, but it still finished much firmer on the day in
London. The currency rose to DM1.7460 from DM1.7240; to Y138.50 from
Y138.05; to SFr1.4750 from Y1.4590; and to FFr5.9150 from FFr5.8325. On Bank
of England figures the dollar's index climbed to 66.6 from 66.2.
The improvement by the dollar was mainly at the expense of the D-Mark, with
the German currency weakening in cross rate trading, particularly against
the Japanese yen. It finished in London at Y79.30 compared with Y80.05
previously.
Figures from the European Commission showed the D-Mark around the middle of
the European exchange rate mechanism, but later in the day unofficial
figures put the German unit second weakest, just above the French franc. The
French currency hit its floor against the top placed Spanish peseta.
Sterling remained fourth strongest in the ERM, on data from the European
Commission, with the pound holding relatively steady despite heavy losses
for Britain's ruling Conservative Party in Thursday's local government
elections.
These results appear to rule out a UK general election as early as June and
have therefore temporarily reduced any political risk in holding sterling.
Dealers believe they may have also delayed further cuts in UK bank base
rates. The Bank of England endorsed the present rate structure in its
operations on the London money market yesterday.
At the London close the pound had fallen 2.15 cents to Dollars 1.6950 while
declining to Y234.75 from Y237.00 and to SFr2.5000 from SFr2.5050, but was
unchanged at DM2.9600 and rose to FFr10.0250 from FFr10.0125. Sterling's
index fell 0.2 to 91.2.
</TEXT>
