<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / International Company News: Manpower declines to Dollars
18,000 after tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANPOWER, the employment group which eventually resulted from the merger of
the UK's Blue Arrow group and Manpower of the US, yesterday reported a steep
decline in first-quarter profits.
Blaming the general recessionary climate on both sides of the Atlantic, the
Milwaukee-based group made Dollars 18,000 after tax in the first three
months, excluding any goodwill amortisation.
This compared with an Dollars 8.69m profit in the same period a year
earlier.
Revenues in the period amounted to Dollars 681.3m, against Dollars 669.3m.
The company had already warned that, after a fairly sharp earnings tumble in
1990, it would break even or even possibly show a small loss in the first
quarter.
It did not provide a detailed break-down of the figures, but said that the
Manpower International subsidiary contributed profits of Dollars 7.96m,
against Dollars 23.4m last time.
Mr Mitchell Fromstein, chairman, noted that the first quarter is usually
light in terms of revenues and profits, and claimed that revenues had held
up relatively well, at least preserving the group's market share.
The company is currently redomiciling to the US, from Britain.
Yesterday, its shares, listed in ADR form, eased  1/8 to Dollars 12.
</TEXT>
