FT  04 MAY 91 / International Company News: Continental cuts payout on
profit dip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KATHARINE CAMPBELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONTINENTAL, the German tyre manufacturer, proposes to halve its dividend to
DM4 for 1990 following a sharp drop in earnings occasioned by the dismal
state of the world tyre market.
Net profits fell to DM93.4m (Dollars 56m) last year, after DM227.8m in 1989.
The earnings setback had been accurately foreshadowed in the defence
document Continental drew up at the end of last year in the course of its
attempts to ward off advances from Pirelli of Italy.
Arguing for its independence and against Pirelli's merger proposals
Continental pointed out that it was still making money - even if largely in
the non-tyre activities gathered into ContiTech.
The Pirelli group, which accounts in guilders, suffered a loss of Fl 9.3m
(Dollars 4.94m) loss for 1990, with no dividend being paid for the per-iod.
Group turnover edged up 2 per cent to DM8.55bn, while other details of the
1990 performance await the annual press conference on May 14.
In February, Mr Ignolf Knaup, the finance director, forecast an improvement
in the current year, with turnover rising to around DM9.5bn, helped both by
acquisitions and by internal growth.
Net profits should reach around DM100m for 1991, according to Mr Knaup.
