<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Scottish TV edges ahead helped by rise in
programme sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE PEARSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INCREASE of more than 40 per cent in programme sales was the main factor
allowing pre-tax profits at Scottish Television, the independent television
contractor for central Scotland, to edge up from Pounds 11.11m to Pounds
11.23m in 1990.
Sir Campbell Fraser, chairman, said that 'within the context of a testing
year', the company performed well in every area of its activities.
The results come just days before the deadline on May 15 for companies to
submit bids to the independent television commission for the new ITV
franchises.
Sir Campbell said the company was putting the final touches to its
application for central Scotland. If reappointed, he was looking forward to
'a return to better days' in 1992.
He noted that, among other attributes, the company had a strong balance
sheet, improving share of advertising revenue, increasing programme sales
and costs under tight control.
Advertising revenues were up only 2 per cent at Pounds 89.05m (Pounds
87.32m), but Sir Campbell said ITV as a whole stood still. By contrast
programme sales and services rose strongly to Pounds 18.24m (Pounds 12.91m).
Total turnover was Pounds 114.08m (Pounds 103.78m).
The pre-tax line was, however, depressed by a rise in the Exchequer levy to
Pounds 6.8m (Pounds 4.04m): 'not the first time', Sir Campbell noted, that
the charge had been increased at a time of difficulties for the industry.
However, compared with the previous year, profits were helped by charges of
only Pounds 558,000 (Pounds 3.15m) for voluntary early leavers and
retirements and reorganisation.
The final dividend is lifted to 23p (20p) for a total of 28.75p (25p).
Earnings per share were 62p (61p).
See Lex
