<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / UK Company News: BP attacks Government on ACT reduction
scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH PETROLEUM hit back yesterday at the Government's decision to squash
its plans to issues shares in its Britoil subsidiary in an attempt to reduce
its Advance Corporation Tax bill.
Last month, BP announced that it was working on a complex plan to issue
so-called stapled shares as a way of saving about Pounds 150m this year in
ACT payments.
However on Thursday night the Government announced that it would be
introducing legislation into this year's Finance Bill to stop such schemes.
'We think our scheme was fair and legal and that we were very open with the
Government and Treasury over what we wanted to do,' BP said yesterday.
'The law allowed us to do this and in the interests of shareholders we hoped
to recover Pounds 150m. The Government's legislation is specifically
designed to block our scheme.'
BP said that despite this setback it would continue lobbying the Government
concerning the issue of Advanced Corporation Tax. BP is one of a number of
large companies which are unable to recover all the ACT they pay on
dividends because the bulk of their profits is earned overseas.
ACT can be set off against UK corporation tax but companies such as BP do
not earn enough profits in the UK to use up the backlog of prepaid ACT. The
total amount of unutilised ACT in the UK is thought to be as much as Pounds
750m.
</TEXT>
