<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Bush rejects charges over Iranian hostages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush yesterday angrily rejected allegations that he visited
Paris in 1980 to help the Reagan presidential campaign strike a deal with
Iran to delay the release of American hostages until after the election that
November.
Mr Bush's denial - the first time he has specifically addressed the issue -
came amid calls in the US press and among Democrats in Congress for an
inquiry into the persistent but unproven allegation that the Reagan team
manipulated the hostage issue to ensure President Jimmy Carter's defeat in
1980.
The story has gathered momentum since Mr Gary Sick, a senior Carter
administration official, set out the case for an inquiry in a lengthy
article last month in the New York Times which drew on interviews with
multiple sources in eight countries in four continents.
Journalists, historians and politicians alike have never been able to show
that Iran's agreement to release the 52 Americans in Tehran, just minutes
after the inauguration of President Ronald Reagan in January 1981, was
anything more than coincidence.
This week, the State Department fuelled speculation by denying a visa to Mr
Abolhassan Bani-Sadr, former Iranian president, who wanted to visit the US
to promote his book which repeated the allegations. The department reversed
itself yesterday, and Mr Bani-Sadr was said by his US publisher to be taking
the next available flight from his exile home in Paris.
Mr Bush sounded testy when confronted with reporters' questions that he
brokered the deal with Iran to delay the release of the hostages in return
for later arms sales from Israel. He called the stories 'rumour mongering'
and 'sickening', denying point-blank that he visited Paris.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, press secretary, sought to kill the story by calling Mr
Sick, a respected Middle East expert who served in both the Ford and Carter
administrations, 'the Kitty Kelley of foreign policy' - a reference to the
controversial biographer of Mrs Nancy Reagan.
Although respected newspapers such as the New York Times and Washington Post
have expressed support for an inquiry, the mood among Democrats appears
mixed - particularly in the absence of the proverbial 'smoking gun'.
Mr Tom Foley, House speaker, said the accusations merited investigation. But
Mr Lee Hamilton, an influential member of the House foreign affairs
committee, said after an informal meeting with Mr Sick this week that 'we
have reached no conclusions about what (he) said, and certainly no
conclusions about what follows.'
Privately, someDemocrats worry that some of the sources of the allegations
are Israelis who say they used to work for Mossad, the Israeli intelligence
service.
Foreign policy observers in Washington note that the allegations have
resurfaced after the Gulf war - the very time when the Bush administration
would like to exert pressure on Israel to be more co-operative in the Middle
East peace process.
</TEXT>
