<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Turkish border closure hampers aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TURKEY closed its main border route into Iraq for more than three hours
yesterday, cutting the overland flow of allied relief to Kurdish refugees in
the region, US military officials confirmed.
The incident came as Turkey decided to expel a British reporter whom it
accused of 'biased' reporting. The article by Robert Fisk, correspondent for
The Independent, alleged that Turkish troops were stealing aid supplies.
In Ankara, Mr Morton Abramowitz, US ambassador to Turkey, sought to play
down the significance of the border closure.
He said the problem was caused by Turkish construction workers, due to enter
northern Iraq to work on setting up allied refugee camps. They arrived
without proper documentation, he said.
'This is not something we are trying to single out. Please understand that
these are the sort of problems that occur in any big operation.
'We are not talking about major problems, we are talking about problems that
constantly arise in any operation, especially one of this magnitude,' he
said.
The incidents came after a rise in tension between Turkey and the allied
forces working to move hundreds of thousands of Iraqi Kurdish refugees back
to their homes.
The closing of the border and the expulsion of the journalist appeared to
reflect the anger felt by Turkey's military over its loss of control of
operations within its country, and the critical portrayal of Turkish
soldiers in the foreign media.
The Independent said Turkish authorities had declared that Mr Fisk, defence
correspondent Christopher Bellamy, staff reporter Phil Reeves and Richard
Wayman, a freelance photographer working for the paper, persona non grata
and had withdrawn their press credentials.
Meanwhile the United Nations took the first formal step to obtain the
payment of compensation by Iraq under the ceasefire terms, creating a
special fund to be financed from the country's oil revenues.
But in a report to the Security Council, Mr Javier Perez de Cuellar,
secretary general, acknowledged that ensuring financing for this
compensation fund would be among the most technical and difficult tasks to
be undertaken by its proposed commission of experts in finance, law,
accountancy, insurance and environment damage-assessment.
Among the options he suggested to ensure that Iraq honoured its pledge to
make reparations was the setting-aside of a percentage of the market value
of oil exports or the acquisition of a physical share of such exports for
direct sale on the market on the fund's behalf. 'It must be recognised that,
in all probability, it may be some time before Iraq is able to resume oil
exports,' he said. Also, at any given time, the value of claims approved by
the commission, a subsidiary organ of the Security Council, was likely to
exceed the fund's resources.
The EC and the British government are to co-finance 20 'mobile support
teams' to help Kurdish refugees return to Iraq, David Gardner reports from
Brussels.
Volunteers from the UK's fire and ambulance services, hospitals and
Territorial Army, are to be deployed for three months, financed by Ecu2m
(Pounds 1.39m) from Brussels and Ecu0.9m from London.
The EC has already mounted three other joint operations in northern Iraq -
with France, Belgium and the Netherlands - as part of its commitment of
Ecu150m in aid to the Kurds. Joint action is seen as a way of reducing
growing aid demands on a badly strained budget.
</TEXT>
