<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 91 / Survey of Franchising (5): Banks warm to those lower risk
options - Raising Finance / There are special packages on offer for the
right team
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOULD-BE franchisees who have teamed up with an established franchisor can
expect a favourable deal from their bank manager when they approach him for
start-up finance. Many of the UK banks offer special franchise packages
which reflect what they see as the lower risks attached to a franchised
business.
Nevertheless, two years of very high interest rates have reduced the influx
of new entrants to the franchise sector. The broad middle range of
franchisees who have to take out a bank loan secured on their home to fund a
franchise in the Pounds 50,000-Pounds 120,000 range have been hard hit.
The high cost of borrowing; the reduced value of their home to be used as
security; and the difficulty of selling their home to relocate to a district
where a franchise is available have combined to cut the numbers of potential
franchisees.
The wealthy investors and businessmen buying into highly priced hotel and
fast food franchises - often taking up several outlets at a time - have not
been so adversely affected. Nor have the individuals paying out up to Pounds
20,000 for a van and a set of tools to carry out car repairs or domestic
cleaning. Applicants for what are sometimes called job franchises can often
finance entry from redundancy pay or savings.
For franchisees who do need to turn to a bank for finance the big four
clearing banks and the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) have specialist
franchising departments. Lloyds Bank has had a franchise department for the
past five years and has a head office team of three specialists. National
Westminster Bank claims to have been the first into the market with the
appointment of a franchise manager in 1981 and it has a team of 12 people in
the UK. The bank has lent more than Pounds 200m to franchisees over the past
10 years, virtually without loss, according to Mr Peter Stern, senior
franchise manager.
Mr Stern contrasts the enthusiasm of the UK banks for franchising with what
he sees as the relative neglect of the sector by the banks in the US.
Sometimes franchising and licencing activities - both of which can involve
issues such as brand name and trade mark protection - are combined.
NatWest's franchise department also handles retail licencing - where a
company allows others to use its retail formula without going as far as
fully-fledged franchising - while the RBS's franchise team also deal with
technology licencing.
Somewhat unorthodox competition for the established banks emerged just over
a year ago when AIB Bank (formerly Allied Irish Bank) teamed up with
Commercial Union Assurance and the Centre for Franchise Marketing, a
consultancy, to offer franchise finance. This arrangement, known as the
Franchise Alliance, was intended to help the two financial partners prise an
opening into a market dominated by the four large clearing banks.
With the promise of a decision on finance within 48 hours and the offer to
visit would-be borrowers at their home or premises instead of requiring them
to come into a bank, the alliance has financed just over 350 franchisees,
according to Mr David Taube of the Centre for Franchise Marketing. Funds
have been provided to franchisees of established organisations such as the
Body Shop as well as to newly-formed franchises, he says.
The banks are convinced enough of the additional security provided by the
franchise formula to increase the ratio of finance they will provide
compared with the sums available to other businesses. NatWest and Royal Bank
of Scotland, for example, will provide twice the sum invested in the
franchise by the franchisee compared with its normal lending ratio of 1:1.
Propositions must be proven franchises which can pass the banks' vetting
criteria.
Even franchised businesses have their financial limits. 'Invariably, if a
local branch manager has been persuaded by a franchisee to provide him with
100 per cent finance, the franchisee struggles,' says Mr Stern.
As well as vetting the franchisee, the bank looks closely at the franchisor.
It assesses the success of the franchisor's pilot operation, if the
franchise is a new one, his management experience and his finances. This
ensures the company is strong enough to develop a franchising chain.
Of the two-thirds finance which NatWest provides, it would normally expect
security for 50 to 60 per cent though if less security was available it
might still go ahead by lending under the government's Loan Guarantee
Scheme. The balance of the lending would be unsecured. The bank takes no
security from the franchisor though it does expect the franchisee to allow
it to talk to the franchisor if the franchisee does not perform
satisfactorily.
With an estimated 5 to 6 per cent of franchisees failing each year the 2:1
lending ratio and the security taken on the amount loaned combine to reduce
the bank's risk to just 1.5 to 2 per cent each year, Mr Stern calculates.
Although the banks frequently establish close links with franchisors they
emphasise that providing finance for a particular franchise does not imply
the bank's formal endorsement. The franchisee is still expected to carry out
his own checks on the soundness of the business he is taking on.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
