<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / T&amp;N seeks Pounds 119m to reduce debt and modernise plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
T&amp;N, the UK automotive components and general engineering group, is raising
Pounds 119m (Dollars 204m) to reduce debt and fund its modernisation
programme, as well as cutting a further 2,500 jobs.
The money will be raised in a one-for-four rights issue at 140p a share.
This comes little more than a year after a Pounds 127m, one-for-three cash
call at 150p, which was related to the Dollars 190m acquisition of JP
Industries, the US automotive parts maker.
JPI brought in Dollars 176m debt, which drove up T&amp;N's borrowings to Pounds
248m by last December, giving debt-equity gearing of 49 per cent. Mr Colin
Hope, chairman, said one reason for the issue announced yesterday was to
reduce that ratio to less than 30 per cent.
Some market disappointment at the move was reflected in an 11p fall in the
share price to 163p.
The job losses follow cuts of 1,800 last year and will bring T&amp;N's total
workforce down from 42,000 in December to fewer than 40,000. When the group
announced its 1990 results in March, it provided for another 600
redundancies this year, but warned that the cuts were an ongoing process.
Mr Hope said the brunt of the cuts would again be in the UK, where T&amp;N has
16,000 workers, and on the automotive side. Over two years, redundancies
would cost the group about Pounds 21m.
As UK component suppliers have had their margins squeezed by sharp falls in
sales volumes, the 'big six' (Lucas Industries, GKN, Pilkington, BBA, T&amp;N
and BTR) have shaken out about 5,000 jobs over the past 12 months. Warnings
had already been issued that 1991 would see several thousand more disappear.
Mr Hope said the labour cuts, spread over 150 factories in several
countries, were also the consequence of investment in more efficient plant.
Capital spending would be kept at more than Pounds 80m this year, compared
with Pounds 89m in 1990. 'We want to maintain our investment programme and
keep a sound balance sheet,' he said.
He warned that the first-half results would be well below the Pounds 46.1m
pre-tax recorded in last year's interims. They would be more like the second
half of last year, when the taxable amount fell to Pounds 24.4m and earnings
per share were little more than 4p.
With interest costs rising to Pounds 15.6m in that half and an interim
dividend of 3.6p to try to match, Mr Hope agreed there had been some concern
about ratios other than the gearing.
The board did, however, declare its intention to maintain the total dividend
for 1991 at 10.85p. Mr Hope expected a second-half improvement as the
benefit of lower costs came through and demand began to pick up.
Last year, when T&amp;N's pre-tax profit fell 16 per cent to Pounds 70.5m on
sales of Pounds 1.25bn, sharp declines were registered in continental Europe
as well as in the UK. T&amp;N is more exposed to Fiat, Renault and Peugeot in
Italy and France than to the busier German makers. Mr Hope said while the UK
deteriorated further, France and Italy had improved a little.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
