<PROFILE>_AN-BEIAWAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Garcia rejects allegations of corruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NOBODY in Peru arouses such intense political passions as former president
Alan Garcia, writes Sally Bowen in Lima. So allegations against him of
massive corruption, unveiled last week in the country's congress, have all
the makings of a long-running political drama. Mr Garcia is alleged to have
deposited some Dollars 50m in foreign bank accounts during his five-year
presidency, which ended last July after the victory of Mr Alberto Fujimori.
Mr Garcia called the allegations 'a scandalous fabrication,' and warned that
they would prove to be a 'political boomerang'.
Mr Fernando Olivera, the deputy heading the parliamentary commission which
has been investigating relatively minor discrepancies in Mr Garcia's
declared income and house purchases, made the allegations before a full
congressional session. He read reports from two North American investigation
services.
One of the investigators, Kroll Associates, has a track-record of probing
the finances of dictators such as Panama's General Manuel Antonio Noriega,
the late Ferdinand Marcos of the Philippines, and Iraq's President Saddam
Hussein. Their preliminary report on Mr Garcia alleges the existence of an
account in his name at a now-defunct savings and loan in Dallas, Texas. Larc
Investigative Services of Miami gives alleged details of 'several six-figure
deposits (totalling approximately Dollars 50m) made between 1986 and 1989,'
apparently in Mr Garcia's wife's name. Funds were subsequently transferred
to various international financial institutions, it claims. Mr Garcia calls
the charges an 'irresponsible and delinquent' attempt by the right 'to teach
a lesson to the man who confronted the banking system. Why don't they just
kill me once and for all?' The ex-President and his wife have legally
empowered the presidents of the congress and supreme court to gain access to
any bank accounts in their names and to withdraw any funds discovered.
</TEXT>
