<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Steady advance inspired by Wall St
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A STEADY advance in London share prices yesterday was inspired by Wall
Street's good performance overnight and, to a lesser extent, by the start of
the new session as well. Domestically minded investors waited for the
results of UK local elections and found little direction from a mixed bag of
corporate news.
The market shrugged off the latest in the series of rights issues. The
Pounds 119m cash call from engineer T &amp; N surprised sector specialists.
Market strategists see more on the way. They reiterated their view that the
stream of rights issues - worth Pounds 1.1bn in April and more than Pounds
300m in the first two days of May - would be a drag on share prices.
Such cash as was being invested in the UK was directed primarily into the
less speculative sectors, such as food retailers, utilities and banks.
Better than expected results from Wellcome triggered heavy buying of the
stock and made it the sharpest riser of the day in the Footsie.
Mr Richard Kersley at BZW saw the interest in retailers as more than just a
response to the Appeal Court ruling earlier in the week which opened the way
for more shops to open on Sundays. He said it also reflected a conviction
that when the economic recovery came it would be consumer-led. Its scale
would still be modest, however, perhaps half that of the growth in
consumption in the late-1980s, widely seen to have stoked up inflationary
pressures at the time.
The interest in defensive vehicles also allowed investors to take into
account the widely divergent views on when recovery would begin in earnest.
Even the most bullish of broking houses sees little recovery in the near
term, and there are several prepared to pencil in the summer of 1992 rather
than the last quarter of 1991.
Analysts were wary of committing themselves on the very short term as well.
County NatWest believes that politics will be the key to sterling and gilts
over the next week. Mr Bob Semple at County said that while yesterday's
local elections would help indicate whether the government had succeeded in
reducing the vote-losing effect of the poll tax, London shares would still
look to New York for inspiration. He added that the US stock market, where
prices already discount a recovery, was more vulnerable to downgradings than
London, especially if US inflation figures came in above expectations.
Today's US employment figures will provide the next test of sentiment.
True to form, the 42-point rise overnight on Wall Street underpinned
London's opening. Hopes for more to come pushed the FT-SE 100 index to a
high for the day, just before Wall Street opened, of 2,539.3.
While US stocks did indeed stage early gains, they were not enough to stave
off scattered selling in London. The Footsie drifted back to end at 2,530.7,
up a net 22.3.
Turnover reached 516.6m, continuing the week's gentle rise. The extra
activity yesterday was said by traders to have been the result of funds
taking the opportunity to sell selectively into the rally. These levels of
trading leave brokerages uncomfortable: turnover is more than 100m shares a
day below the levels seen in the March bull market and barely two-thirds of
the Pounds 1bn a day seen as a profitability benchmark by the City.
The brewery sector was the softest. Aided by bid speculation, it has bucked
the market trend for several days. But such thoughts were forgotten as
attention turned to the more measured rally elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 40
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1617</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBAFQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / London Stock Exchange: Wellcome helped by drug sales
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WELLCOME was the best performer of the day among FT-SE 100 stocks in heavy
trading. Investor enthusiasm was triggered by the company's interim results.
In particular, the sales of virus drug Zovirax reminded the market that it
should not see the company as dependent on Aids treatment Retrovir.
Analysts raised their forecasts for full year profits and reiterated buy
recommendations. BZW pointed out the company's increased margins, adding
that they are still below Glaxo's. County NatWest raised its full year
profits estimate from Pounds 345m to Pounds 370m, saying that 'Wellcome is
likely to be among the fastest growing FT-SE stocks in earnings terms over
the next few years'.
Wellcome shares ended at the day's high of 582p for an advance of 63.
Turnover reached 6.1m.
T &amp; N cash call
The second cash call by automotive component and engineering group T &amp; N in
just over a year surprised the market. It was perceived as opportunist, and
not necessitated by the current level of gearing, which is generally seen as
not being too high. The upshot was a fall of 11 in the shares to 163p.
T &amp; N proposes to raise Pounds 119m through a rights issue, having called on
shareholders in March of last year for Pounds 130m. Further job losses were
also announced and the Pounds 7m cost of the rationalisation caused analysts
to lower both profits and earnings per share (eps) forecasts. County NatWest
now expects eps of 12.4p, down from 14.2p.
Allied-Lyons lower
Some of the speculative froth on Allied-Lyons shares yesterday was blown
away by reports that US brewer Anheuser-Busch, one of three rumoured
predators, was not interested in acquiring the UK group. Short-term
operators saw this as a signal to realise profits and reinvest in less
volatile equity leaders.
The resulting sales allowed marketmakers to balance short book positions and
the Allied share price slipped to close 12 down on the session at 561p.
Trading volume was high at 5.4m shares traded.
Allied is expected to report lower annual profits on May 14 owing to foreign
exchange losses of Pounds 150m. Confirmation is also awaited of the early
retirement of both the chairman and chief executive.
BOC lost 5 to 565p as Mr Alastair Nisbet of UBS Philips &amp; Drew changed his
recommendation on the stock from buy to hold and cut his profits forecast
for the current year by Pounds 15m to Pounds 335m. He blamed currency
movements, the recession in Canada and recent poor results from US chemicals
companies for his decisions.
British Gas recovered 2 to 238p on heavy turnover of 10m as some broking
firms took the view that the underperformance of Gas shares both before and
following the acceptance of the Ofgas tariff proposals had gone far enough.
The exploration success in the Gulf of Mexico continued to drive the oil
majors higher, with BP a further 6 up at 357p on 6m. Shell lagged behind,
closing only 2 firmer at 527p, restrained by more hefty selling from
overseas. Turnover in Shell was 6.5m.
The market continued to ponder the chances of Elf and Enterprise engaging in
a joint venture to acquire Occidental's North Sea assets, and then indulging
in an assets swap which would involve Enterprise acquiring Elf's 25 per cent
stake in the UK oil group.
County NatWest, which regards Enterprise as 'good value', said it thought
such a deal unlikely because it would create a large ACT (advance
corporation tax) problem for Enterprise. Kleinwort Benson believed a swap
'might occur', adding that 'if so, Enterprise will be a better balanced
company but its share price will be lower'. Enterprise improved 2 to 561p.
Water shares extended their rally for much of the day but came off the best
levels just before the close, when a series of big trades at prices well
below market levels flashed up on the Seaq delayed ticker.
The late business was thought to have represented more unravelling of the
Water Package units, a trend much in evidence in recent weeks as the market
has taken on board the implications of the cessation of trading in the
Package on July 12.
The late deals included a line of 1.6m Thames Water, traded at 313p (Thames
closed 11 higher at 320p), and a 1.7m line of North West, traded at 296p
(the stock ended 12 stronger at 305p). Earlier in the day a block of 1.7m
South West Water went through the market at 306p; South West settled a net 4
up at 303p. The Water Package, where turnover reached the equivalent of 5m
of the underlying shares, picked up 98 to Pounds 3068.
Much of the improvement in sentiment in the sector has been attributed to
switching out of stocks such as British Gas into the waters. And water share
prices are now thought to discount a poor performance by the Conservatives
in yesterday's local elections.
Hoare Govett issued a note on the entire utilities area, highlighting the
exposure to political, regulatory and environmental risks. County NatWest,
however, pointed out that the performance of the water issues in April was
not as grim as daily price movements implied. Over the month the sector
index showed a marginal rise while the equity market was broadly unchanged.
County said that the run-up to an autumn general election should be smooth;
at current levels the sector is looking oversold.
There was strong activity in the banks, where switching operations and
straight buying, both domestic and overseas, was sharply focused on NatWest,
which advanced 11 to 340p on heavy volume. Lloyds also saw big turnover but
the shares underperformed, ending only 2 up on the session at 337p.
The fall-out from Allied-Lyons brought the good run in Bass to a halt and
the stock closed 17 easier at 982p. Grand Metropolitan, on the other hand,
warmed to dollar influences and rose 9 to 821p, while clearance of a line of
stock overhanging the market put Guinness up 10 to 918p. The latter is James
Capel's star buy for May.
Ratners fell 12 1/2 to 165 1/2 p as reports began to filter back from
analysts visiting its US operations. The suggestion was that US sales had
not picked up as strongly as had been hoped following the end of the Gulf
war.
Turnover in Tesco swelled to 22m shares as the company bought 7.3m for its
employee profit sharing scheme. UBS Phillips &amp; Drew paid institutions 297p
per share and Tesco closed 9 higher at 296p. Kwik Save rose 5 to 592p on
indications that Aldi, the German discount supermarket group, may now be
looking towards markets in eastern Germany, rather than the UK, where it
recently established a foothold.
A two-way pull developed in Asda, which added 1 1/2 at 122 1/2 p on 11m, as
some institutions continued to reduce their holdings following the profits
downgrades and reports of weak trading. Other investors were buyers on the
basis of the shares' recent underperformance. Argyll rose 11 to 316p on
signs of switching from Tesco.
Several broking houses lowered profits forecasts for automotive components
group GKN and this exerted pressure on the shares, which weakened 6 to 361p.
Bletchley Motor, the multi-franchised distributor, went 10 higher to 90p on
a buy recommendation from Kleinwort Benson. Analyst Mr Jeremy Allen said the
shares were standing at a 'significant discount' to the sector average, have
a high yield of over 13 per cent and an attractive asset backing of 205p per
share.
Coats Viyella was well supported, and as the price rose so the values of its
all-paper and mixture of cash and shares offers for Tootal were enhanced.
Coats settled 6 higher at 148p and Tootal a penny firmer at 85p.
The recent run in Flexello Castors &amp; Wheels was abruptly reversed by the
warning that the interim results would be significantly worse than those of
last year. To strengthen the company's financial and commercial position,
discussions are taking place which might lead to an offer being made. The
shares finished 12 down at 97p.
Land Securities retreated 10 to 519p on 2.2m on worries that it may report a
larger than expected fall in net asset value in its final results due later
this month. Some brokers have already lowered their forecasts to around 685p
per share, against 867p last time.
NEW HIGHS AND LOWS FOR 1991
