<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The Property Market: Recession shows eerie similarities to
1970s
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS the severity of this property collapse becomes increasingly apparent,
comparisons are being made with the 1970s crash, writes Vanessa Houlder.
'The similarities between 1972-74 and 1988-91 are immense,' says Savills,
the surveying firm.
'Setting the last five years against the boom and slump of the 1970s, the
profile of returns since 1985 has been uncannily similar; a three-year
upswing to peak at 30 per cent, followed by a precipitous drop,' says the
Investment Property Databank, a research body.
Some parallels are striking. In both cases, a credit boom fuelled some heady
years of growth, which led to a sharp hike in interest rates and a recession
exacerbated by international pressures.
In some respects, the crash of the 1970s was far worse than that of the
1990s (so far). 'In the first year of the 1970s slump, rising yields knocked
a third off real capital values; and a further 10 per cent in the following
year,' according to IPD. 'Bad as we think it is, the yield shift of 1989-90
is not this sharp'.
The knock-on effect on the banks has been less severe. Whereas the 1970s
crash triggered a secondary banking crisis, this time banks appear more
resilient and property lending accounts for a smaller proportion of their
loan books.
Furthermore, the large property companies, some of which went close to the
brink in 1974, now have far stronger balance sheets. So far, receiverships
have been far fewer than the first half of 1974.
In addition, the economy was in worse shape in the 1970s putting more
pressure on rents than is expected this time. 'Our current assessment is
that rent growth in the early 1990s will be more favourable than that from
1975 to 1978, especially in real terms, because the recession is expected to
be briefer and shallower,' says IPD.
That said, many in the property industry are experiencing harder times than
in the 1970s. 'Never can I think of a time when conditions have been so
adverse for property investment and development,' says Sir Nigel Mobbs, one
of the industry's most experienced figures.
The scale of overborrowing and overbuilding in the industry at present
dwarfs anything seen before.
The more manageable inflation problem of the 1990s is perhaps a mixed
blessing. Although it signified a far greater malaise in the economy in the
1970s, it also helped to get the developers off the hook thanks to its
effect on real interest rates and the replacement costs on building. It may
take some time before building costs equal those incurred in the heat of the
construction boom.
Perhaps the most worrying feature of the industry's current predicament is
that there are few obvious buyers of the property overhanging the market. In
the 1970s, it took four years for the surplus property to be absorbed. There
is every chance it will take even longer this time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
