<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Trinkaus operating profits
climb 30%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KATHARINE CAMPBELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUSSELDORF
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PARTIAL operating profits at Trinkaus &amp; Burckhardt, the Dusseldorf-based
bank controlled by Midland Bank of the UK, rose 7.9 per cent last year to
DM80.8m (Dollars 45.6m), with a weak domestic stock market and low turnover
taking the edge off growth in fee generating business writes Katharine
Campbell in Dusseldorf.
Total operating profits, which include gains from the bank's account
trading, rose by more than 30 per cent. However, a large proportion of this
rise is due to profits from business transacted in the two previous years,
Mr Herbert Jacobi, senior managing partner, said.
Following German accounting conventions, profits arising from interest rate
and equity warrant transactions are not booked when the bank takes in its
fees, but rather when the warrants mature, typically between one and two
years after they are issued. This occurs although Trinkaus hedges its
positions and runs only a minimal credit risk.
As the results show, the bank continues to consolidate its position as a
leading provider of innovative capital market instruments, often packaged
with derivatives components. With a fifth of its earnings coming from
clients not with the bank five years ago, the bank says its ability to
provide the range of interest rate and foreign exchange derivatives has been
a selling point.
</TEXT>
