<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: Defence cuts push Hughes
Aircraft into diversification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HUGHES AIRCRAFT, part of General Motors and the leading US defence
electronics company, is resigned to achieving little or no growth in its
military business between now and the mid-1990s.
This is despite expectations in the defence industry that electronics
specialists will be less damaged by declining government spending than
manufacturers of 'platforms' such as airframes.
Mr Michael Smith, Hughes' executive vice-president and chief financial
officer, said yesterday any growth would have to come from civilian sectors,
which last year accounted for barely a fifth of the company's Dollars 7.8bn
sales.
The outlook he presented during an interview was notably pessimistic on US
defence budget prospects but, in contrast to widespread caution in the
industry, bullish about opportunities for diversification making use of
military technology.
'A lot of companies have tried and failed, and we have looked hard at some
of them,' Mr Smith said. Hughes, however, had a much greater breadth of
technology than most other defence manufacturers.
The company plans to reduce its dependence on the military from 78 per cent
last year to 60 or possibly 50 per cent by the middle of the decade. Two
years ago, the figure was around 90 per cent.
Overall sales are expected to grow to about Dollars 10bn, in constant terms,
by 1995, but with military business stagnating at the current level of
Dollars 6bn a year.
Mr Smith said the company expected US spending on defence procurement to
decline more drastically than official forecasts, with annual reductions in
real terms of around 5 per cent 'at least through 1995.'
However, Hughes was well placed to pick up contracts for upgrading existing
equipment.
'After 1992 we think our defence business will actually begin to tick back
up again,' Mr Smith said.
Although its rival, Westinghouse, is supplying the radar for the latest US
fighter project, the Lockheed/Boeing/General Dynamics F-22, Hughes won the
contract for the aircraft's computer processing system.
Expected to be worth about Dollars 1.5bn, this contract opened up a new
business line, with potential spin-offs in both military and civilian
fields.
Plans for new business outside defence included satellite-based
telecommunications, air traffic control, and avionics and landing aids for
civil aircraft. Expertise in power supplies, derived from Hughes' military
radar business, would be used in electric car development with GM and in
diversification into lighting products.
Hughes also aimed to increase its share of the defence market as more
companies dropped out. Unions at TWA, the highly-indebted carrier, together
with the City of St Louis, TWA's main operating base, have filed a motion
asking the US Department of Transportation to stay its ruling on the sale of
its London Heathrow routes, writes Nikki Tait in New York.
The union-St Louis group has already filed an appeal against the decision,
which permitted TWA to sell its three principal London routes to American
Airlines.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1626</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBAFHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: Shares in top Adsteam offshoots
are suspended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK WESTFIELD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE AUSTRALIAN Stock Exchange yesterday suspended shares in the three top
Adelaide Steamship companies, Adsteam, David Jones and Tooth and Co, pending
further information on the confused position of their proposed
reconstruction.
On Wednesday, Adsteam called off its ambitious ADollars 6bn (USDollars
4.6bn) reconstruction in which the companies were to be merged, stating
there was 'little or no equity' for shareholders.
The merger of these three technically insolvent companies would have brought
together their three-way ownership of the profitable Industrial Equity which
owns Australia's most successful retailer, Woolworths.
The position of the banks, owed ADollars 6bn, and the chairman of the
committee overseeing the proposed merger, Mr David Crawford, of KPMG Peat
Marwick, was still unclear yesterday after strong rumours that Mr Crawford
would take over the group as a court-appointed administrator.
Unconfirmed reports yesterday suggested that the banks were inclined to
return to the merger proposal abandoned the day before by the group.
The suspension of the Adsteam shares, however, shows just how far these
companies have fallen. Last year, when the exchange threatened to suspend
trading in the shares after the group resisted a stock exchange demand for a
consolidated balance sheet, former managing director Mr John Spalvins
threatened to make massive legal claims. The exchange backed away.
Mr Spalvins was 'terminated' by his board in March when the group was
obliged to announce a half-year loss totalling ADollars 3.7bn, mainly
through write-downs in the value of group cost shareholdings.
The dramatic fall from grace of this once powerful industrial conglomerate,
which was Australia's largest food producer and second largest employer, has
been a traumatic experience for the investment community.
The All Ordinaries Index dropped 12.6 points yesterday on the news of the
abandonment of the Adsteam merger plan.
Yet, there would be few Australian investors who would not remember the
rapid rise of Adelaide Steamship under the stewardship of its fresh-faced
chief executive, Mr Spalvins, who transformed the sleepy Adelaide tugboat
operator into a formidable investment company from 1980 onwards.
Mr Spalvins introduced a new philosophy to the Australian corporate sector
as he voraciously acquired under-performing companies and turned them into
cash boxes after selling their assets.
He emerged from the corporate backwater of Adelaide in 1980 to acquire the
upmarket department store chain known as David Jones in an audacious share
market raid.
With the dust barely settled, Mr Spalvins turned his guns on the struggling
brewery group Tooth and Co, which he rapidly acquired before selling the
main brewery assets to rival brewer Carlton and United Breweries.
</TEXT>
