<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: Apache buys Amoco unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN A move which will double its reserves and production, Apache Corporation,
the Denver-based oil exploration and production group, is to buy a domestic
business which owns a number of US-based oil and natural gas producing
properties from Amoco, the fifth largest US oil company, writes Nikki Tait.
The main consideration for the transaction comprises Dollars 515m and two
million shares of Apache. Yesterday, Amoco shares fell Dollars  7/8 at
Dollars 53 3/8 , while Apache rose Dollars 2 at Dollars 15 7/8 .
Apache said that the deal means that oil reserves will increase to about 40
per cent of total reserves, compared with 21 per cent at present.
Apache also claimed that total proven and probable reserves of the
properties were around 133m barrels on an oil equivalent basis. They are
located primarily onshore and close to the Gulf Coast, in the Rocky
Mountains and mid-continent regions, and in the Permian Basin.
The package was said to include interests in wells which produced a daily
average of 28,000 barrels of oil and 117m cubic feet of natural gas last
year.
For the much-larger Amoco, however, the properties represent less than 5 per
cent of proven US reserves on a oil equivalent basis. The company claimed
that the sale formed part of 'an ongoing portfolio management'.
