<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: Solitary activist takes on a
giant - A boardroom tussle at Sears, Roebuck
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the right hand corner, the combined boardroom might of retailing and
financial services giant Sears, Roebuck, one of the largest companies in the
US. In the left, the solitary figure of Mr Robert Monks, seasoned
shareholder activist.
A tussle between the two sides over the composition of the Sears, Roebuck
board will come to a head next Thursday when the Chicago-based company holds
its annual meeting. Mr Monks is seeking shareholder support to take up one
of three vacant seats on the Sears, Roebuck board. Sears, Roebuck is
strongly opposing him.
Contested board elections are hardly unusual during the US annual meeting
season: takeover bidders and corporate raiders with large stakes in
companies are increasingly using proxy, or shareholder voting battles, to
exert leverage over managements.
What makes this contest so unusual is the figure of Mr Monks, who owns only
100 shares in Sears, Roebuck and is using the contest as a testing ground
for ideas of the growing US corporate governance movement - the belief that
companies' professional managers should be more accountable to their
shareholders. In particular, Mr Monks' candidacy has focused attention on
the composition of US boards and the methods by which directors are
nominated.
Mr Monks is one of the leading figures in the corporate governance movement,
which includes some of the country's most powerful public pension funds.
Aged 57, and a voluble zealot for the cause, he is a Harvard-educated lawyer
who once headed the US Labor Department's pension programme. In the
mid-1980s, he founded Institutional Shareholder Services, a pioneering
Washington firm that advises pension funds on how to vote their proxies, but
last year he resigned from ISS to set up a new organisation - Institutional
Shareholder Partners. This, he said, would allow him to take a more directly
activist role in pushing shareholder rights issues - and the Sears, Roebuck
campaign is one result.
It comes at a time when Sears, Roebuck is suffering from considerable
shareholder dissatisfaction over its poor financial and share price
performance. The problems centre on its core 104-year-old retailing business
rather than its large financial services operations, which include the
brokerage house Dean Witter Securities. Last summer, the situation was
deemed so serious that Mr Edward Brennan, the group's chairman and chief
executive, resumed direct responsibility for the retailing side and began to
slash costs.
The starting point for Mr Monks' campaign is his observation that the Sears,
Roebuck board - in common with virtually all large US corporations - is a
self-perpetuating body, nominating new directors who are then rubber-stamped
in shareholder elections. He complains that although this passes for
'shareholder democracy,' it does not allow investors to exercise any real
choice and does not produce a board of genuinely independent directors, even
if the nominees come from outside the company.
'So long as an individual 'owes' his membership on a board uniquely to
personal selection by the chief executive officer, he cannot be considered
to be 'independent.''
Applying these principles to the particular case of Sears, Roebuck, Mr Monks
suggests a lack of independent boardroom voices may be related to the
company's 'less than mediocre performance.' His election, he says, would
give the board an independent shareholder perspective and his business
experience - such as the chairmanship of the Boston Company, a financial
services business taken over by Shearson - would allow him to offer ideas
which might help Sears, Roebuck to work better.
For example, he says the company should either reach its target return on
equity or be restructured. These remarks echo suggestions by some critics
that Sears, Roebuck might be better broken up. He also maintains that Mr
Brennan has taken on too many responsibilities for one man and the functions
of chairman and chief executive should be separated.
The Sears, Roebuck viewpoint is very different. The company argues Mr Monks'
primary interest is in using it as a laboratory for his ideas of corporate
governance and his presence on the board would distract it from its central
goal of improving the group's financial performance.
Whatever the merits of the case, the odds seem stacked against Mr Monks. One
reason is an initiative Sears, Roebuck took in March which blunts his
campaign. It announced that it would be strengthening the role of outside
directors, initially by cutting the size of the board from 15 to 10 and
eliminating the seats of four company employees. The only inside director
will now be the Sears, Roebuck chairman.
The smaller number of directors also has the effect, given Sears, Roebuck
voting methods, of making it harder for a candidate such as Mr Monks to win
a contested election.
Mr Monks' limited financial fire power is also a factor. While Sears,
Roebuck has budgeted Dollars 5.5m for the proxy contest, Mr Monks is using
only Dollars 250,000 of his own money and he says this has limited his
ability to reach smaller Sears, Roebuck shareholders. So, too, has the
company's refusal to give him access to its shareholder list - and legal
action it is taking against him to support this action. He also complains
that the tortuous regulations of proxy contests - which the Securities and
Exchange commission is considering reforming - has restricted his ability to
manoeuvre.
The composition of the company's shareholder list will weigh against him.
Some 35 to 40 per cent of its stock is held by institutional investors and
he may pick up a significant protest vote here. For example, the California
Public Employees Retirement System, the largest public pension fund in the
US, has been so dissatisfied with Sears' performance that last January it
send a delegation to demand change from Mr Brennan.
But even institutional backing may not be that forthcoming: Mr George
Reagan, from the large Teachers Retirement System of Texas, expresses some
admiration for Mr Monks, but says he may vote against him because he is
worried about public funds, which are ultimately responsible to politicians,
playing such an activist role in corporate governance. 'Would you want the
(British) prime minister to be running private enterprise?' he asks.
It will be even harder for Mr Monks to win the backing of smaller
shareholders, who hold around 40 per cent of the company's shares, while the
trustees of Sears, Roebuck's employee benefit funds - which own a
particularly large 23 per cent of the company - can be virtually guaranteed
to vote against him.
Mr Monks admits to being a little pessimistic. 'My situation is distinctly a
long shot,' he declares. In the event of victory, he will try to recoup his
expenses from the company, but if he fails, he will be Dollars 250,000 out
of pocket.
Sears, Roebuck suggests that he will have other compensations - immense free
publicity for his business and for a book he has written on corporate
governance, due to be published immediately after the proxy battle.
Mr Monks, wearing the mantle of an idealistic zealot for better corporate
governance, says he hopes his campaign will at least have focused attention
on some important issues.
That it may do, for while the Sears, Roebuck battle seem unlikely to lead to
a rash of such initiatives, it could help focus US investor attention more
closely on the selection of the people running companies  - supposedly in
shareholders' best interests.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24 Photograph Edward Brennan, he will be the only inside
director (Omitted).
</PAGE>
