</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNTLEIGH Technology, the USM-quoted medical equipment manufacturer, lifted
taxable profits from Pounds 936,000 to Pounds 1.62m for the year to
end-December.
The 73 per cent surge was achieved on turnover increased to Pounds 17.44m
(Pounds 14.87m), with more than 75 per cent of sales going abroad.
Mr Julian Schild, finance director, predicted further profit increases.
'With an ageing population and the government under pressure to spend more
on increasingly sophisticated medical equipment we believe we are in a
recession-proof business.'
The healthcare division represents 85 per cent of overall turnover. Earnings
per share expanded by 78 per cent to 12.61p (7.1p).
Net borrowings rose to Pounds 2.7m (Pounds 1.8m), representing 52 per cent
of shareholders funds. Net interest charges increased to Pounds 221,000
(Pounds 184,000).
The increase in debt was due mainly to a heavy capital expenditure programme
of Pounds 2.6m on new factories and machinery. A further Pounds 970,000 was
spent on research and development.
A proposed final dividend of 1.75p lifts the total by 1p to 3p.
Mr Schild said the group would continue to develop and market new products
in medical preventative techniques. It has recently launched a new version
of Flowtron DVT, a pneumatic compression devise to prevent blood clots
developing during surgery.
