<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Buying spree in Polly Peck shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Polly Peck International have been the subject of a concerted
buying spree in recent days and weeks, pushing up the price ahead of
reconstruction plans due to be announced shortly.
Institutional and large private investors have been approached by
individuals saying they are buying on their own account or for overseas
trusts, whose beneficiaries are not disclosed. There has also been a wave of
buying in Zurich, where Polly Peck is still quoted. The shares have been
suspended in London since last September.
Institutions said that they believed the buying could reflect the creation
of a substantial interest by Turkish or northern Cypriot interests.
Mr Asil Nadir, Polly Peck's Turkish Cypriot chairman, said in a statement
through his lawyers yesterday that he did not know anything about the recent
share buying. 'He is co-operating closely with the administrators and the
indications from them prior to the creditors' meeting on 24 May are very
encouraging,' the statement added.
News of the buying surge is known to have caused concern to the authorities
in London, especially since reconstruction plans for Polly Peck are due to
be announced by the group's administrators within days. An optimistic report
from the administrators would boost the prospects for Polly Peck
shareholders.
The shares, which reached a peak of 450p, fell to 108p before being
suspended last autumn. About a month ago, institutions and private
individuals were approached with offers of 10p a share. That has now risen
to 12p per share in new approaches.
Under UK rules, transactions in the shares of suspended companies are still
allowed to take place, although members of the Stock Exchange are not
allowed to take part in any dealing.
In Zurich, meanwhile, several million shares are understood to have changed
hands in recent weeks, pushing the share price from around 10p to 22p.
Several private investors with large numbers of shares have been telephoned
from London by a man calling himself Mr Richards. He offered to buy blocks
of 50,000 shares or more at 12p a share. Mr Richards says he is buying for
his own account rather than for another investor.
</TEXT>
