<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Ford and Vauxhall attack claim on prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD AND Vauxhall, the UK car market leaders, yesterday attacked figures
produced for the Monopolies and Mergers Commission claiming that some
pre-tax car prices charged in the UK are over 50 per cent higher than in
certain other European markets.
The controversial figures produced for the MMC by Ludvigsen Associates, the
UK-based automotive consultancy, are expected to provoke a fierce dispute as
the MMC finalises its monopolies inquiry into the distribution and pricing
of new cars in the UK.
The MMC has already provisionally concluded that at least two so-called
'complex monopolies' exist in the supply of new cars, which 'prevent,
restrict or distort' competition in the UK market.
The Consumers' Association claimed yesterday that the Ludvigsen report
vindicated its 10-year campaign claiming that cars 'can be thousands of
pounds cheaper in continental Europe compared with the UK.
'The details of the MMC's work blow out of the water the arguments of
manufacturers that price differences are due to special factors - such as
exchange rate movements, specification differences and discounts.'
Mr Paul Tosch, chairman and managing director of Vauxhall, which controls
about 16 per cent of the UK new car market, said the company had
commissioned its own independent research which cast serious doubts on the
Ludvigsen findings.
'We do not agree with the Ludvigsen figures. We have not finished our
discussions with the MMC, but on a broad basis we are very competitive in
the UK. In some cases prices in the UK are in the lower range compared with
the rest of Europe.'
Vauxhall also questioned the methodology of the report prepared for the MMC,
which had sought to establish actual transaction prices through telephone
calls to dealers, in contrast to the Vauxhall study, which had been based on
invoices of actual deals.
Mr Tosch said Vauxhall had largely stayed within the allowable 12 per cent
price band laid down by the European Commission for car price differentials
between national markets in Europe, except for a couple of 'rogue' models.
Mr Lindsey Halstead, chairman of Ford of Europe, which captured 25 per cent
of UK new car sales last year, said differences in pan-European car prices
were 'affected by a complex series of issues. There are some factors that
the Ludvigsen study did not even consider'.
