<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: CS Holding
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Is the bad news finally out of the way at CS Holding? Zurich seems
tentatively to have thought so yesterday; the shares, initially down some 2
per cent on news of a catastrophic year at CS First Boston, rallied by more
than twice that, to SFr2,160, as the market mulled the refinancing plans.
These are ingenious. Floating off part of Credit Suisse may or may not
soften the Swiss legal mind on the subject of bank capital adequacy. But it
will certainly raise money, as will the forthcoming loan issue, the
equivalent of up to 25 per cent of group capital; this is obviously not true
of the one-for-20 warrants for un-issued shares. Flexibility is what
chairman Rainer Gut says the group will gain; it seems a mild term for a
potentially large recapitalisation.
With one leap Rainer was free? Only up to a point. The group will gain
underlying capital strength, but properly consolidated accounts could have
made the ground look still firmer, though these are very explicit figures by
old Swiss standards. But the explanations are less impressive than the
numbers. The group had no such exceptional Gulf exposure that CS First
Boston should have entered the league of biggest loss-makers. Nor is the
news that CS First Boston had a profitable first quarter persuasive given
the bull market in Wall Street.
What remains to be proved is that Mr Gut was right to buy out CS's former
Boston partners in catastrophe, and that the group now has the talent and
controls in place to avert a repetition. It may not be until we get the 1991
report that we will begin to know.
</TEXT>
