<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: T&amp;N
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is easy to be rude about T&amp;N's rights issue, the fourth cash call in five
years. The shares have underperformed the market by 50 per cent since 1986.
The proceeds do little more than cover the next two annual dividend
payments. And the yield on the new paper works out at 10.3 per cent. With
the balance sheet not seriously stretched, the market is entitled to be
cynical.
T&amp;N, however, still deserves the benefit of the doubt, and not merely
because it is one of those companies still trying to keep UK manufacturing
competitive. Trying to escape the long shadow of asbestos claims, it has
undergone a radical transformation, with a growing reputation for the
quality of its automotive and engineering products and big orders from Ford
in Europe and Nissan in the US. The problem is maintaining the high levels
of R and D and capital spending which made this possible at a time when
markets, notably automotive markets, have collapsed around the world.
T&amp;N's recent earnings record is miserable - minus 9.5 per cent compound over
the last five years. But if it emerges from the current recession with lower
costs and a sustained reputation for quality there is scope for a sharp
reversal of trend. The trouble for investors hoping for more than a good
yield is that the dividend cover (1.2 times) will take time to repair.
</TEXT>
