<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The Lex Column: A matter of interest
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,530.7 (+22.3)
Global interest rate policy is still made in Washington, as far as Europe's
equity markets are concerned. Share price gains yesterday were spread across
the board: 2 1/2 per cent in France, 1 1/2 per cent in Germany, 0.9 per cent
in London. Equity markets are evidently half-persuaded that where US
interest rates lead, others will follow, no matter what is said at G7
meetings.
UK short-term interest rates, indeed, are discounting a half percentage
point cut in base rates by June, with May 17, the date of the next RPI
figures, a popular candidate. None the less, London's rise yesterday was
accomplished on unexciting volume, only a little better than that of recent
dismal sessions. Monday, in particular, was one of the worst days for
activity since the rally started.
By historical standards, it can be argued that London is not dangerously
costly; or even (looking at the ratio between long-term interest rates and
equity yields) that it is rather cheap. That ratio is sensitive to
inflation, though. It has moved in its current range only since inflation
took off in the mid-1960s. If inflation were now to move permanently to a
lower level, the normal range would shift downwards too, making today's
level less of a bargain.
Hopes remain of a flood of cash takeover bids to offset the Chinese water
torture of rights issues; corporate lawyers talk of merger work stacking up
in their offices, waiting to burst upon the world once preparation is
completed. So far, that is just talk; until it becomes more than that,
London will continue to bounce between New York's side-effects and the local
election hangover.
</TEXT>
