<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The revolt of the Names: Reforms at Lloyd's insurance market
are unlikely to satisfy those members who are facing huge losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sad thing is how gullible we were,' says a Name at Lloyd's of London,
reflecting on the 'exquisite lunches' and 'glib promises' that persuaded him
to become a member at the insurance market in 1978.
Today the Name - the individuals who commit a minimum of Pounds 250,000 to
back underwriting activities - is one of several thousands facing potential
bankruptcy as a result of the losses sustained by the market. The sharply
deteriorating financial position stems mainly from US liability suits and
claims arising from natural disasters.
Names, who are formed into more than 350 groups, or syndicates, have
unlimited liability for the losses they incur. For Lloyd's, the disillusion
of many Names and the damaging publicity from current court cases has cast a
cloud over the market's future as it seeks to halt the decline in its share
of specialised commercial insurance and reinsurance.
As Lloyd's prepares to close its accounts for the 1988 year, in line with
its three-year accounting system, it is expected to record an overall loss
of at least Pounds 150m. Its premium income for the same period amounted to
about Pounds 6bn.
In 1989, while premium income seems likely to stay at about the same figure,
losses could be as much as Pounds 1bn, according to Mr John Rew, co-author
of Chatset's Lloyd's League Tables, a comprehensive guide to the market. By
comparison, in the golden years of 1986 and 1987, Lloyd's made overall
profits of Pounds 649.5m and Pounds 509.2m, a return of 17.5 per cent and
12.1 per cent of premium income.
Names are bearing the brunt of the downturn. Some estimates suggest that
several thousand could become insolvent this year. 'The fact is that a
horrendously large number of people are going bankrupt,' says the chairman
of one group of Names considering legal action to recoup losses. The
financial difficulties of the Names are being aggravated by the recession,
with a depressed housing market making it difficult to raise cash by selling
property.
Dr Mary Archer, chairman of the Lloyd's Hardship Committee established last
year to help Names in acute difficulties, and the wife of former
Conservative party chairman Mr Jeffrey Archer, says the number of appeals
for help has accelerated recently to about 150. She adds: 'I have to say
that I would expect the case-load this year to be very heavy.'
Until January 1990, Names had merely to show personal wealth of Pounds
100,000, and so it is people who joined the market before this date that
have been most severely affected.
Although Lloyd's membership carries an aura of wealth, many Names are middle
class and joined the market because, says Mr Rew: 'They are strapped for
cash. They need the income from Lloyd's for extras like school fees.' In a
good year, Names could expect a return of at least 12 per cent on their
investment.
A fundamental and continuing attraction of membership has been that Names
need only lodge 30 per cent of their Pounds 250,000 commitment with Lloyd's.
They can continue to collect interest, dividends or rental income on the
remainder. 'Over the years people have done pretty well. The money was easy
to put up,' says one Name who works in a UK merchant bank and who joined the
market in 1985. 'I just had to show property of Pounds 40,000 and a bank
guarantee for Pounds 60,000.'
Many Names, especially those who joined between 1977 and 1986 when Lloyd's
membership nearly tripled, have insufficient capital to pay their share of
current losses.
Last week the personal columns of one national newspaper carried an
advertisement that conjured images of Dickensian social disgrace. 'Ruined
Name at Lloyd's,' it read. 'Must earn. Have wife. Will travel.'
As the losses start to mount, more and more Names are refusing to pay up.
Some Names are said to be 'protecting' their assets. There are reports that
some Names have signed over their property and paper wealth to their spouses
or have even shifted their money abroad. Increasingly, Names are resorting
to legal action. Members of six syndicates have issued, and in some cases
served, writs alleging that the negligence of their agents and underwriters
is to blame for losses they have incurred.
The court cases will be long. Much of the litigation stems from the market's
exposure to US liability risks - asbestosis and pollution - which were not
well understood at the time when syndicates contracted the original policies
in the 1940s, 1950s and 1960s. Claims on these policies have resulted from
court decisions of the 1970s and 1980s, in which US judges interpreted the
law in a way that was more generous to policyholders than had been the case
20 years before.
To complicate matters further, much of this 'high risk' liability business
was insured and reinsured in London at a time when the rules governing
Lloyd's market were not as stringent as they are today.
From the market's point of view, the possibility of future claims on many of
these US liability policies cannot be ruled out. The uncertainty means that
syndicate managers have been unable to assess the scale of future claims and
more than 90 underwriting years have been left open - syndicates' accounts
cannot be closed. Since Names cannot leave Lloyd's while they are on an
'open year', many hundreds are, in effect, trapped.
A look at some of the outstanding and potential cases against Lloyd's will
serve to illustrate the problems the market now faces:
Last week, a civil case brought by 33 Names - members of four syndicates
formerly managed by Oakeley Vaughan Underwriting Agency, now in liquidation
 -against the Corporation of Lloyd's, began at the High Court in London.
This is the first time in the market's 300-year history that a case against
Lloyd's has actually gone to court.
The Names allege Lloyd's failed properly to supervise the market in the
period between 1980 and 1982 when, as a result of financial mismanagement,
the Oakeley Vaughan syndicates made heavy losses.
A civil case involving more than 880 Names who were members of the Outhwaite
syndicate 317/661 in 1982 is set to go to court in November. The Names are
suing various agents at Lloyd's to recoup insurance losses of more than
Pounds 200m. In 1982 Outhwaite reinsured the asbestosis exposures of about
20 Lloyd's syndicates. The action against Outhwaite alleges that the
acceptance of so big a risk by Outhwaite without any corresponding
reinsurance constituted negligent underwriting. The Names also allege that
the members' agents that funnelled their Names on to the Outhwaite syndicate
were also negligent.
About 570 Names who backed syndicate 553, managed by the Warrilow agency,
face losses of about Pounds 80m and have issued writs against the agency and
members' agents, alleging negligence in the way business was conducted. The
case is expected to come to court next year.
Names on two syndicates, 90 and 334, managed by Pulbrook Underwriting
Agency, face some of the heaviest individual losses. Two hundred and eighty
Names who were members of Pulbrook syndicate 334 in 1985 lost about Pounds
30m and have issued writs against the syndicate's managing agent and
members' agents.
A further 250 Names who were members of Pulbrook syndicate 90 face losses of
about Pounds 40m and have also sued members and managing agents. Names on
syndicate 90 allege that Pulbrook Underwriting Management, which managed the
syndicate, was negligent in failing to make full business disclosure to its
reinsurers, thus enabling the reinsurer to deny liability. Winchester
Bowring, the broker which placed the reinsurance contract, is also accused
of negligence.
Late last year over 100 Names who backed syndicates 106 in 1985 and 108 in
1986 issued writs against the syndicates' managing agency, John Poland, and
members' agencies.
Next week, more than 2,000 Names who face potential losses of Pounds 300m as
a result of the failures of syndicates managed by the Feltrim agency are
expected to decide whether to pursue legal action. If they go ahead, they
will push the total number of litigating Names to more than 2,000, a figure
approaching 10 per cent of the market's total membership. An official at one
members' agency believes half the market's membership of 26,500 could be
involved in court action before the end of the year.
Though all these cases involve individual allegations of negligence or
misconduct, a more fundamental problem provides the backdrop to them. Even
without the losses sustained in the US, changes in the structure of the
market itself would have made it a riskier place in which to invest over the
past 10 years.
During the 1980s the rate of underwriting profit that a typical Lloyd's
member could expect to make fell by more than a third, says Mr David Newton,
who runs an investment advisory service for overseas Names.
After the introduction of a new self-regulatory regime at Lloyd's in 1982,
syndicates and their agents incurred expensive new legal obligations which
increased the cost of doing business in the market. Salaries also increased
sharply. As a result, the fees that some Names pay to their agents have
doubled over the past 10 years, says Mr Newton.
Names also run more risk now. They can still deduct any underwriting losses
against other income to reduce tax bills, but this is much less of an
advantage than it was during the 1970s when the top rate of personal income
tax was 98 per cent. More important is the fact that while only a minority
of syndicates made losses in the early 1980s, more recently the market as a
whole has been affected as a result of a combination of factors.
First, premiums have been depressed as a result of competition between
Lloyd's and international companies; second, Lloyd's syndicates have
recorded a string of billion-dollar losses as a result of natural disasters;
and third, there has been a continuing deterioration in results from US
liability business because of the impact of pollution claims.
In the past Names have typically relied on the advice of their members'
agent, taking little interest in the results of the syndicates which they
were backing. But because of the current harsh conditions they are less
likely to succeed if they do not keep a close eye on their affairs. They
must look at 'membership as a true business proposition,' says Mr Newton.
But does the market provide enough of the right kind of information to make
such an approach possible? And are its regulatory mechanisms adequate to
protect Names? Lloyd's practices in two areas - the mechanisms to monitor
premium income accepted by syndicates and the amount of information
disclosed to Names - have both improved since 1982.
But despite these improvements in the market's practice, there are still
serious grounds for concern. One Name, who became a member of Lloyd's in
1984, says: 'They are not disclosing the truly significant business. I would
hazard a guess that Lloyd's is 15 to 20 years behind the Stock Exchange in
its requirements of disclosure' of business information.
The chairman of Lloyd's Mr David Coleridge, who took over late last year, is
receptive to criticism. His election was significant in several ways, not
least because he represents the growing power of the bigger agency groups,
such as Sturge and Merrett, whose interests are best served by a more stable
relationship between a richer, more selectively recruited set of Names and a
more professional market.
A task force, on which Mr Anthony Haynes, the chairman of the Association of
Lloyd's Members, as well as a several leading figures on the market is
sitting, is conducting a through review of operations. Mr Haynes is
optimistic that its report could lead to improvements. But for those
embittered Names who face bankruptcy, reform could come too late.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
