<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Leading Article: No FT, no comrades
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORKERS' flag is deepest pink, or so we might conclude from Wednesday's
Labour party election broadcast on television.
'The Financial Times says: 'Today the Labour party looks like the competent
party with sound ideas on local government. The Conservative party has no
policies.' ' Thus went the first of no fewer than four ringing endorsements
for Labour from this newspaper.
The attentive viewer might have noticed that on the subsequent three
occasions the phrase 'on local government' had disappeared. But it would
have taken a viewer with considerable powers of memory to recollect the
context of this remark, from our political columnist, Joe Rogaly. It was as
follows:
'Labour governance of the poor by the unemployable has given us nuclear-free
zones, gender-based support groups, and the visible ruination of perfectly
good schools by infesting them with sub-standard teachers with not a thought
in their cotton-wool minds. The cost, reflected in local taxation, has
soared beyond the reach of public acceptability. Yet today Labour looks like
the competent party with sound ideas on local government; the Conservatives
are the knuckleheads.'
Perhaps for its next broadcast, the party might like to take highlights from
another recent FT column, by Samuel Brittan. He wrote: 'Unfortunately, it is
still not possible for market economists to support Labour with a straight
face.' There is no reproduction fee.
</TEXT>
