<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Observer: Crazy rhythm
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ruddy-cheeked Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of France's Front National, was in
prime ranting form for the extreme right-wing movement's annual Joan of Arc
rally, but his choice of music becomes ever more eccentric.
After a presidential campaign conducted to the stately chorus of the
Children of Israel from Verdi's Nabucco - ironic, considering the regularity
with which Le Pen is convicted for anti-semitic remarks - the theme song at
the rally was Elgar's Land of Hope and Glory.
Although preferable to Keep the Home Fires Burning, it was a curious way to
commemorate the Maid of Orleans.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1657</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBAELFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Observer: Messy affair
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WPP's Martin Sorrell has done valiant behind the scenes work in the run-up
to the boardroom coup at the Budgens supermarket chain, where he was the
only non-executive director. It was apparently his idea to bring in
Charterhouse to give the Budgens board independent advice, and WPP's Hill
and Knowlton public relations team was imported to add professionalism to a
messy affair.
True, Sorrell's role in extending the contracts of the top Budgens
executives after some abysmal results was surprising. But generally he seems
to have behaved as a model, if not holier-than-thou, non-executive director.
It is all a bit ironic. Sorrell, like erstwhile friend John Fletcher, is an
entrepreneurial Harvard MBA once able to persuade banks to lend him loads of
money for takeovers. Now Fletcher has been given the boot, will the
institutions turn their gaze on WPP?
Its shares have collapsed; the millenium may be over before it pays its next
ordinary dividend; and its board badly needs some new non-executive
directors.
Perhaps the Budgens affair was Sorrell's dress-rehearsal. Perhaps, too, more
will be revealed in WPP's accounts due at the month end.
</TEXT>
