FT  03 MAY 91 / Observer: Desk reading
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What's so special about chief executives' desks? SQ Mile magazine, a new
quarterly glossy for City folk, has decided to find out. It has come up with
the rather quirky idea of handing a psychologist pictures of the desks of
captains of industry and finance, and asking him what they reveal about the
owner.
For instance, who's this?
'He is an analyst, first and foremost, a man of formidable intellect and
powers of cognate penetration. He reaches out and clutches the heart of the
matter in The Meeting, his assistants or enemies have long since lost their
nerves and minds. Never to his face, some unkind observers have described
him as a 'bit of a cold fish'.'
Answer: Sir Eric Parker, chief executive of Trafalgar House. Oddly enough,
SQ Mile belongs to Simon Broackes, son of Trafalgar House's ritzy Sir Nigel.
The magazine is also getting the psychologist to answer readers' queries.
The next, to be shrinked in the summer issue, is: How can I tell if my
managing director is mad? The questioner is 'a chairman'.
