FT  03 MAY 91 / Observer: Braced up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Barclays Bank has bagged another brace of corporate status-symbols for its
board. It now has a Japanese banker (Shijuro Ogata), and a high- flying
Dutchman (Jan Peelen), to display beside its erstwhile chancellor of the
exchequer and former civil-service head of the UK Treasury.
A big bank needs big directors and Barclays now has same in abundance.
Admittedly it's nowhere near as international as JP Morgan, with its well
connected international council and a top executive where foreign-born
bankers outnumber Americans 3-2. But it's streets ahead of the rest of the
UK clearers.
Barclays' choice of its new directors is interesting, given their Far
Eastern bias. Ogata was deputy governor of the Bank of Japan, and Peelen is
responsible for Unilever's East Asian and Pacific business.
The explanation may be that, having failed to crack the North American
market, Barclays is anxious to beef up its weak representation among the
world's fastest growing economies. For a bank clearly intent on thinking
big, perhaps the next step might be a Far Eastern acquisition.
Standard Chartered?
