<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Arts: From the Court of Ranjit Singh - A Sikh's taste in the
exhibition 'Warm and Rich and Fearless'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Traditionally the Sikhs have been regarded as a people of limited aesthetic
sensibility. Rather in the way that the English perceived the Scots, they
were deemed tough farmers and fighters of legendary bravery with no time at
all for the liberal arts - at least until Ranjit Singh forged an autonomous
Sikh kingdom in the first years of the 19th century.
Warm and Rich and Fearless, which appears to be the first comprehensive
exhibition in Britain or India devoted to Sikh painting and applied art, at
Cartwright Hall in Bradford until June 2, should finally lay that myth to
rest.
BH Baden Powell described the Sikh artists' use of colour as 'Warm and Rich
and Fearless', a description perhaps as appropriate to the Sikhs themselves.
An introduction to Sikh history and culture is offered in the exhibition
catalogue, beginning with Nanak (1469-1539), the founder of the faith and
the first of its 10 gurus. The 100 or so exhibits - drawn from the V&amp;A, the
India Office Library, the Royal Collection and private collections - take up
the narrative some 300 years on.
Despite limitations of size and cost, and the quite understandable absence
of such evocative Sikh treasures as the Koh-i-noor diamond (then the largest
in the world) and Ranjit Singh's golden throne (in the V&amp;A) it is a
rewarding and enjoyable show.
Ranjit Singh's court provided the stability and patronage for the flowering
of Sikh art, its prosperity and lavish spectacle as much a magnet to the
Pahari artists of the Punjab hills as to foreign visitors. The Maharaja had
a taste for the grand gesture and a sensibility to the natural world -
ordering a 21-gun salute in honour of the moon, say, or halting meetings of
state to watch the formation of the monsoon clouds.
Yet the splendour of his court life, and the extravagance of such
peccadillos as drinking wine (forbidden by Sikh law) mixed with powdered
pearls, are at striking variance with his own unprepossessing and relatively
modest appearance.
Contemporary accounts emphasise his small stature and badly scarred face,
smallpox having blinded one eye and paralysed an arm and a foot. We find him
astride a prancing milk-white horse with hennaed fetlocks, his head shrunk
into his shoulders, his garb rich but simple. Prime minister Raja Dhian
Singh out on a hawking expedition cuts far more dash.
Such vibrant gouache miniatures of the mid-19th century are the glories of
the show. Appropriately they have been selected to represent artefacts also
on show or to reveal aspects of the Sikh character and way of life. A
manifestation of the egalitarianism that underpins Sikh culture, for
instance, is suggested by Raja Hira Singh's attendant who stands before his
master without the cringing deference found in Mughal painting. Two
cultivators - with water diviners? - allude to the Punjab as the granary of
India.
From the same set comes a painting of two Akalis - fiercely militant ascetic
Sikhs - portrayed bare chested in their prescribed shorts, with weapons
tucked into their conical turbans and brandishing clubs. Examples of the
terrifying razor-sharp steel quoits or Chakras that, when not spinning
through the air to fatal effect, were worn on their turbans, are here too.
Horse necklaces - and human jewellery - chain-mail armour and the
magnificent damascened shields of intricate koftgiri work are represented in
pigment and reality, the latter a speciality of Sikh craftsmanship until the
British banned the manufacture of weaponry in the Punjab.
Gradually a Sikh idiom emerges out of the synthesis of Mughal and Jain
painting. Curving lines and languor are abandoned in favour of sharper
angles, often provided by oversize parasols, and a new tension more
appropriate to Sikh manliness.
That said, there is a vestigial delicacy and fastidiousness in some images,
in the elegant poses, the bejewelled and spindly furniture based on English
Regency models, and in the delicate, stylised blooms.
Sikh painting shows a particular and sometimes penetrating portraiture. No
attempt has been made, for instance, to hide the charmlessness of Kaharak
Singh, Maharaja 1839-40. He resembles nothing so much as the frog-prince who
has not yet been kissed.
Sadly, we have only Hasan al-Din's uninspired portrait of the Maharaja
Duleep Singh, painted a few years before the Punjab was annexed by the
British in 1849 and the boy-king was forced to give up his throne, his
kingdom, the Koh-i-noor and, temporarily at least, his religion.
The watercolours and miniature portraits on ivory that follow, executed by
Indian and European artists, are disappointing. The exceptions are the
lithographs after drawings made by the Russian Prince Alexis Soltykoff in
the 1840s. Far more rewarding than the later watercolours are the golden
folk embroideries - the Phulkaris and Baghs - that continued to be made by
the Sikh women of the Punjab until early this century. Their deliberate
asymmetrical designs employ stylised motifs of everyday life - peacocks,
ears of wheat, coins, chillies, even railway engines.
Other textiles range from a Kashmir coat with lavish embroidery to Sikh silk
battle standards said to have been used in the final Anglo-Sikh war, and to
the contemporary shimmering, gauzy silk scarves confected by the
British-born Sikh Sarbit Natt, their handpainted designs drawing from the
geometries of traditional Phulkari.
The modern white nylon lace and even nastier synthetic red and gold brocade
used in the display of the manuscript of the Dasam Granth, the writings of
the last Sikh guru, are lamentable even without the contrast.
Modern Sikh art is also given a cursory nod, in the form of two paintings
recently given to Bradford. Paris-trained Amrita Sher-Gil, part Hungarian,
part Sikh, is represented by a haunting Portrait of a Woman of 1936, its
earthy tones reminiscent of the Buddhist cave paintings at Ajanta, and
Arpana Caur with his recent Time Image 2.
The exhibition can be seen at Walsall Art Gallery February 7 - March 27,
1992.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
