<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / UK News (Employment): UK and Ireland have longest work hours
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AND Irish employees work longer hours than all other European
workers and the UK has among the lowest levels of statutory protection in
areas such as night work, rest periods and weekend work, a report to be
published next week will show.
Only the UK and Denmark, of the 17 countries examined, place no statutory
limit on the normal number of hours a worker may be asked to work in a week.
Limits in other countries vary from 48 in Germany and Italy to 39 in France.
According to the report, the UK is also the only country in western Europe
with no legal entitlement to paid annual leave. Entitlements in other
countries range from three weeks in the Irish Republic to five weeks in
Austria.
Britain is also unusual in having almost no restrictions on night work
hours, weekend working, rest breaks and overtime working, and no provisions
for employee participation in organisation of working hours. In nearly all
countries, the law provides for limits on overtime and all except the UK
have legislation providing for weekly rest periods.
The report coincides with attempts by the EC to establish European-wide
norms over working time by introducing, for example, rest periods between
shifts and possibly a maximum night shift of eight hours in any 24-hour
period.
The attempts are being resisted by the government, which believes employers
should decide.
The report found that the average British employee works 229 days a year,
compared with 231 in Ireland, 225 in Sweden - the average in Europe as a
whole - and 220 in Germany, the lowest for a European country.
Working Time In Europe. Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury Place,
London N5 1QP. Pounds 40.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
