<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Appeal fails to exclude evidence in Guinness trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO FORMER City merchant bankers facing criminal charges in the forthcoming
second Guinness trial have failed to exclude evidence they gave to
Department of Trade and Industry inspectors investigating the Guinness
affair.
Mr Roger Seelig, former corporate finance director at Morgan Grenfell, and
Lord Spens, former director of corporate finance at Henry Ansbacher, had
argued that it would be wrong and unfair to admit the evidence at the trial,
since the inspectors had not cautioned against self-incrimination.
Dismissing their appeal against a pre-trial ruling by Mr Justice Henry, Lord
Justice Watkins said in the Court of Appeal yesterday that the Crown set
great store by gaining the admission of the evidence, contending that it
amounted to confessions by the two men.
The appeal court upheld Mr Justice Henry's decision that DTI inspectors were
not 'persons . . . charged with the duty of investigating offences' within
the Police &amp; Criminal Evidence Act (Pace) and were therefore not obliged to
caution witnesses.
Lord Justice Watkins said that, even if the inspectors had been
investigating offences, and there had been a breach of the Pace code on
cautions, it would still have been open to Mr Justice Henry to admit the
evidence.
Mr Seelig and Lord Spens, who are likely to try to take their appeal to the
Law Lords, face charges of false accounting and offences under the
Prevention of Fraud (Investments) Act over their alleged involvement in an
unlawful share support operation mounted by Guinness during its takeover
battle for Distillers in 1986.
The trial, already postponed since January, is due to start this month but
is likely to be delayed further.
Lord Justice Watkins said Mr Seelig alleged that there had been a conspiracy
between the inspectors, the DTI, the Serious Fraud Office and the police
that the inspectors would use their statutory powers not for the purpose for
which they had been appointed, but illegitimately to build a criminal case
against him.
Mr Seelig claimed that the police had suggested the inspectors' lines of
inquiry and deliberately delayed charging him until the inspectors had
finished interviewing him. He also alleged that the inspectors set out to
trap him into a confession at a time when, if questioned by the police, he
would have had to be cautioned and would have relied on his right to
silence.
The Crown said the inspectors did not have to caution or advise a witness
that he need not answer a question he thought would tend to incriminate him.
To impose any such obligation on inspectors would make their investigations
useless, the Crown contended.
Rejecting complaints that Mr Justice Henry wrongly exercised his discretion,
Lord Justice Watkins said the trial judge had decided that the fairness of
the trial would not be threatened by admitting the evidence, and that no
improper means had been used to force Mr Seelig and Lord Spens to give
evidence that might incriminate them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 13
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1668</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBAEAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Sir George Pollock, an architect of the CBI: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR George Pollock, QC, one of the principal architects and founders of the
Confederation of British Industry, has died aged 90.
Sir George, who ran away from school to join the merchant navy, later worked
as a journalist while he studied for the Bar.
He took silk in 1928 and in 1938 made legal history when he successfully
defended at petty sessions a woman on a murder charge. Previously, people
charged with murder had always been committed for trial at the assizes.
Sir George had a distinguished service record during the second world war,
which included a period preparing teams of saboteurs intended to operate if
Germany successfully invaded Britain.
After the war, he served in North Africa and Italy as a colonel on the
general staff and as chief judicial officer to the Allied Control
Commission.
In 1946, he became recorder of Sudbury but in 1954 left the Bar and began a
new career as director of the British Employers' Confederation.
In 1965, he was one of the guiding lights behind the merger of the
Confederation, the Federation of British Industries and the National
Association of Manufacturers into the Confederation of British Industry. He
later served as a senior consultant to the CBI on international labour
affairs and acted as the representative of British employers on the
governing body of the International Labour Organisation.
He was a member of the Donovan Royal Commission on Trade Unions' and
Employers' Associations from 1965 to 1968. He leaves a son and daughter from
the first of two marriages.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
