FT  03 MAY 91 / Oil tax loophole
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury yesterday announced legislation to close a potential loophole
in the taxation of oil companies.
In a written reply to a parliamentary question, Mr John Maples, economic
secretary to the Treasury, said: 'The government intends to bring forward
measures in the current Finance Bill aimed at preventing the circumvention
of the corporation tax ring fence around profits from North Sea oil by
schemes involving the use of 'stapled stock'.'
This follows a meeting last month between British Petroleum and Inland
Revenue officials to discuss proposals for BP to cut Pounds 150m from its
tax bill by issuing shares in its Britoil subsidiary to BP shareholders.
It planned to offer shareholders redeemable preference shares with a nominal
value in Britoil which would be stapled to BP shares. The shareholders could
then elect to receive a dividend payment from Britoil instead of from BP.
Under the plan BP would have gained the chance to offset the payments of
advance corporation tax it makes on dividends against Britoil's tax
liabilities.
The proposals take effect for distributions to shareholders on or after
yesterday.
