<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Record Pounds 239m Vauxhall profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VAUXHALL, the UK subsid-iary of General Motors, increased its pre-tax
profits last year to a record Pounds 239.1m from Pounds 236.3m a year
earlier.
The company was helped by favourable exchange-rate movements that cut
currency losses to only Pounds 3.2m from Pounds 29.3m in 1989.
Operating profits declined by 13 per cent to Pounds 190.9m from Pounds
219.7m a year earlier, chiefly under the impact of the recession in the UK
new car market.
Mr Paul Tosch, Vauxhall chairman and managing director, warned yesterday
that operating profits would fall further this year in the face of the
continuing steep drop in UK new car demand.
Marketing costs jumped last year as Vauxhall, along with rival car makers,
was forced to increase sales incentives sharply.
The company outperformed the market by holding the drop in UK car sales
volume to 7.7 per cent - 323,054 units - compared with a fall in the overall
market of 12.7 per cent.
Vauxhall, which ousted Rover from second place in the UK car market in 1989,
boosted its share further last year to 16.1 per cent from 15.2 per cent.
Vauxhall's financial performance was supported last year by a 16 per cent
increase in vehicle production to a record 276,000 units. UK-built cars
accounted for 80 per cent of sales, compared with 64 per cent in 1989.
The drop in domestic sales was cushioned by the start of exports to GM
markets in continental Europe.
Exports will be increased to 70,000 this year and will account for close to
30 per cent of Vauxhall's total production from its Luton and Ellesmere Port
assembly plants.
Vauxhall turnover rose last year by 4.9 per cent to Pounds 2.6bn, reflecting
the positive impact of the export programme. Net profits fell 13.3 per cent
to Pounds 181.3m from Pounds 209.1m, as the company faced a full-tax
payment, having exhausted its carry-forward losses in 1989.
It made a Pounds 184m dividend payment last year to GM, after one of Pounds
194.6m in 1989, its first for more than 20 years.
</TEXT>
