FT  03 MAY 91 / Cars rise by a third in 10 years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR and SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of cars licensed to drive on British roads has risen by more than
a third from just over 15m in 1980 to 20.23m last year, according to the
latest annual vehicle census, published yesterday by the Department of
Transport.
During the same period, the number of motor cycles, mopeds and scooters fell
39 per cent from 1.37m to to 833,000.
The number of public transport vehicles increased by 5 per cent to 115,000,
but that is 13 per cent below its peak of 132,000 vehicles in 1988.
Licensed goods vehicles on the road, including most types of lorries and
vans, fell by 4.5 per cent compared with 1989. Figures have varied during
the decade, often in common with the state of the economy.
The number of cars on the road, by comparison, has risen every year since
1980 increasing by 3 per cent in 1990.
Simon Holberton writes: There are still significant benefits for employees
receiving company cars, but the recent tax changes in the Budget mean
companies and employees will have to be much more selective in future,
according to the top pay unit of Income Data Services, a pay research
organisation.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, increased tax charges on company cars by
20 per cent in his March Budget, making employers liable to National
Insurance on the benefit derived by employees.
Tax changes appear to have favoured those who receive a car as a benefit and
handicapped those provided with a car as a working tool.
IDS, 193 St John Street, London, EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
