FT  03 MAY 91 / The Blue Arrow Trial: Share deal considered approved, court
hears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUYING of Blue Arrow shares by County NatWest, County NatWest Securities
and Union Bank of Switzerland took place with legal approval and the
knowledge of NatWest, the parent bank, a former County director had
believed, he told the Blue Arrow trial yesterday, John Mason writes.
Mr James Riddell, a former County financial control director, agreed that
the holdings - taken in the 1987 rights issue - were in three parcels to
avoid the disclosure requirements of the Companies Act. He agreed with Mr
Jeremy Roberts, QC, for Mr Jonathan Cohen, a former County chief executive,
that legal advice had been that that was possible.
Mr Riddell said that, in examining the accounting treatment of the Pounds
70m loss on the holdings after the stock market crash, he had 'always worked
from the framework that everything was legal'.
He presumed Mr Norman Berman, then NatWest's financial control director,
knew everything about the transaction.
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank, UBS Phillips and Drew Securities
and seven individuals deny conspiring to mislead the markets over the
outcome of the Pounds 837m issue.
