<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Signs of a recovery in the modern art market: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE market for contemporary art is being nursed slowly back to health by the
auction houses. On Wednesday night in New York, Christie's sold 53 paintings
and sculptures for Dollars 11m (Pounds 6.3m) but the auction was 25 per cent
unsold by value.
In a comparable sale last year, Christie's sold 11 works for more than
Dollars 1m - on Wednesday only three broke that barrier.
The highest price was Dollars 1.87m paid by the New York dealer Richard Gray
for West Brand, a black-and-white abstract expressionist canvas painted in
1960 by Franz Kline. Christie's had estimated this important work at between
Dollars 2m and Dollars 3m. Bait, by Robert Rauschenberg, made the same sum,
at the bottom of its estimate. Bidders are still light on the ground and
cautious.
The most expensive painting in the sale, Near Parnassus, by Cy Twombly,
which carried an estimate of between Dollars 3m and Dollars 4m, failed to
find a buyer, but Razzmatazz, a large Surrealist work by the Pop artist Roy
Lichtenstein, beat its forecast at Dollars 1.65m.
Sotheby's was selling less important contemporary art in New York on
Wednesday and was happy with a total of Dollars 7.2m and 17 per cent unsold.
Its two days of sales brought in Dollars 28.5m, and by persuading sellers to
accept lower estimates to match the fall in demand it managed to dispose of
most of the lots at the lower price levels.
While contemporary paintings recover, Chinese works of art continue to
command high prices. Sotheby's series of auctions in Hong Kong produced a
total of HKDollars 115.8m (Pounds 8.6m), with 7 per cent unsold.
In the final session, Mist at Dawn, a painting by Zhang Daqian, who died in
1983, sold for Pounds 155,685.
Furniture is one market that has not suffered too badly during the
recession, mainly thanks to buying by Continental dealers. A Belgian dealer
yesterday paid Pounds 13,750, comfortably above estimate, for a late Regency
rosewood breakfront bookcase at Christie's in Edinburgh.
</TEXT>
