<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Evans the candidate fights history
 -Tory prospects for the Monmouth by-election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WOMEN filling envelopes and ticking off charts in the Conservative
central committee rooms in the little market town of Usk must be hoping
Henry Ford was right when he said history is bunk.
Mr Roger Evans, a 43-year-old London barrister with a five-star Welsh name,
is defending a 9,350 Tory majority in this stunningly beautiful constituency
at the bottom end of the Welsh marches, the golden triangle encompassed by
Monmouth, Abergavenny and Usk, where the money of Wales lives.
History is against Mr Evans. Not since October 1945 have the Tories won a
by-election in Wales. And he is the third Mr Evans in a row to fight a
by-election for the Tories - other Evanses lost in Ribble Valley and Neath.
Four years ago, Sir John Stradling Thomas, whose death earlier this year
precipitated the by-election on May 16, saw the opposition divided almost
equally.
Labour was slightly ahead of the then SDP candidate with 13,037 votes to
ll,313. For either Labour or the Liberal Democrats to mount a challenge to
the Conservatives, it must effectively wipe the other out.
The contest has taken on additional significance coming so soon after the
local council elections, and indications are that Labour's 38-year-old Huw
Edwards, another good Welsh name and another outsider - he is a lecturer at
Brighton Polytechnic - is taking votes in handfuls from the Liberal
Democrats' Mrs Frances David, the only local among the three.
An early poll suggested that Labour was winning not only this contest within
a contest but also shading the Tories for first place.
Labour is strongest where the constituency butts on to Newport and the
bottom end of Gwent's industrial valleys, where the voters work, or get a
living from, the nearby Llanwern steelworks or the new town of Cwmbran.
Mr Edwards has not only to hold this base but also win votes from the
disgruntled farmers who live in and around Welsh-sounding villages such as
Llanfoist, Llantilio and Llangwm. Welsh sounding, but very English, with a
lot of the voters commuting to Cardiff and Bristol.
Apart from the market towns like Monmouth, Ragland, Abergavenny and Usk, Mr
Edwards also has to win votes in the neat estates of Chepstow, where the
Severn bridge touches down in Wales, which because of its cheaper housing
has become something of a dormitory for Bristol.
It is a big hill to climb. The poll tax has disappeared as an issue, and the
main concern outside the farms, where there are worries over the drop in
incomes, appears to be the future of the health service, which Labour is
working to the full.
Strangely, the Conservatives appear to campaigning in a low key, almost
offhand. Welsh secretary Mr David Hunt has visited the constituency, as has
party chairman Mr Chris Patten, but there is no evidence of the urgency
needed if the party is not to suffer another Ribble Valley, where a much
larger majority went up in smoke.
Visually, too, there is a strange apathy among the Conservatives. As a
country area the Tories normally put their candidate's window bills on
posts, rather like estate agents' boards, along the roadside. In 1987 they
were everywhere. Now, in most places, they are heavily outnumbered by the
For Sale signs outside the houses of those seeking to move on.
By contrast, Labour's headquarters in a former school in Chepstow is
bursting with life. Not only are many big names paying a visit - Mr Neil
Kinnock, Mr Jack Straw, Dr Jack Cunningham, Mr Tony Blair, Ms Glenda Jackson
 -but backbench MPs aplenty are there.
Both the Greens and Plaid Cymru, the Welsh Nationalists. are represented by
Mr Mel Witherden, who has refused to be photographed in one of the many
markets in case it offended his vegetarian supporters. Presumably, he would
be happy with the farmers in their cabbage fields.
If Mr Evans is looking for an omen there is one that might just come in
handy.
When the Tories last won a by-election in Wales, all those years ago, it was
in Monmouth. The winner, the redoubtable Peter Thorneycroft went on to
become Chancellor of the Exchequer and chairman of the Conservative party,
and held the seat for 21 years.
If he had known that perhaps even Henry Ford might have drawn a different
conclusion.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1681</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Scotland lays plans for business: The issues facing the new
enterprise bodies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Crawford Beveridge is the latest government appointee to wrestle with the
'Scottish phenomenon' - the fact that Scots run big businesses the world
over, not least in England, while in the home country entrepreneurship is
sluggish.
Mr Beveridge is an example of the phenomenon. He is also the man responsible
for the machinery that could tackle it. He was born 44 years ago in
Edinburgh and has spent most of his working life abroad in senior managerial
jobs with US electronics companies. Recently he returned to Scotland from
California, where he worked for Sun Microsystems, the computer workstation
maker which has expanded greatly since its creation in 1982.
Mr Beveridge is chief executive of Scottish Enterprise (SE), the new body
that has taken over from the Scottish Development Agency and the Training
Agency to run business development and training in Scotland. Many of its
powers are in the hands of 13 local enterprise companies (Lecs), the
Scottish equivalent of the training and enterprise councils (Tecs) in
England.
True, SE operates from the old Glasgow offices of the SDA but the
similarities end there.
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, eager to encourage the Lecs with their
private sector boards, and anxious to compensate them for big cuts in
training funds this year by the Department of Employment, has urged SE to
allocate as much as possible of its budget to the Lecs.
SE gave all but 17 per cent of its Pounds 430m budget to the Lecs and admits
it has left itself rather short. 'It leaves us at some risk,' Mr Beveridge
says.
SE dispenses money to the Lecs and authorises how they spend it. It also
still has the strategic development responsibilities of the old SDA, such as
attracting inward investment through the Locate in Scotland bureau, planning
industry-wide initiatives and handling large property and environmental
improvement projects. Whereas the Lecs drafted their business plans last
autumn, SE is still working on its own first-year plan.
'We'll be OK for money on Locate in Scotland but short on property and
environment, as well as on development finance for investing in companies,'
Mr Beveridge says.
He points out that recession is reducing investment opportunities of all
kinds, and so far the SE core staff is between 60 and 70 below its
theoretical strength of 430, because SDA staff have left or moved out to
Lecs while some civil servants from the Training Agency have refused to
join. Morale is said to be low.
Mr Beveridge does not believe that the Lecs will be able to spend all the
money allocated. Several are starting from scratch, and in recessionary
times projects involving the private sector tend to be slow to go ahead.
He will review the Lecs' spending progress each quarter. Mindful that the
Treasury requires official bodies to spend their budgets within the
financial year, he will then 'enter negotiations with them' - the Lecs are
independent companies - 'to move money around to where it is most likely to
be spent,' including the SE core.
In Inverness, Highlands and Islands Enterprise has succeeded the Highlands
and Islands Development Board and has a smaller-scale structure similar to
Scottish Enterprise, with nine Lecs scattered from Shetland to Argyll. Much
more power has been retained at the core here.
A veteran of the HIDB says: 'Our Lecs are very small and inexperienced and
they need a lot of help from us.' The Scottish Office makes Highland Lecs
obtain authorisation from HIE if they wish to spend more than Pounds 15,000,
whereas the limit for SE's Lecs is Pounds 250,000.
Mr Iain Robertson, the 40-year-old new chief executive, another expatriate
Scot who saw an advertisement for his new job in the Financial Times while
working for British Petroleum in Cleveland, Ohio, wants his Lecs to have
more independence. 'The whole point of the change is to put power into the
hands of the communities so that they can no longer say: 'No one ever asked
us, the decisions are taken in Inverness or Edinburgh.' I'm determined the
Lecs will get more autonomy as things go on.'
Still, he admits that only about 25 per cent of HIE's budget is initially
going to Lecs, although further allocations are being held in reserve. Most
of the HIDB staff have transferred to HIE, including Mr Robertson's
predecessor, so the shake-up has been less traumatic than at SE. Others say
the old guard from the HIDB have dug themselves in to preserve
centralisation.
HIE has already drawn up its strategic plan, which recognises that the
population of the Highlands is rising for the first time for a century and
that the big development projects of the past, such as an aluminium smelter
at Invergordon, near Inverness, survived for only a few years, leaving high
unemployment. 'People are coming back and we've got to provide jobs for
their children that are in tune with the place,' says Mr Robertson, looking
at small-scale industry, tourism and fish farming.
Back at SE, Mr Beveridge's preoccupations are with strengthening indigenous
business and developing a long-term strategy. 'There is much more indigenous
business going on here in Scotland than I thought there was looking from
outside,' he says. 'And there's a fantastic number of smart people.
'But there are no Sun-sized new Scottish companies,' he says, referring to
his California days. 'And the boundaries of the ambitions of the small
companies often seem to stop at Carlisle. Not many have a world view, or
even an EC view. Something stops them from having these worldwide
ambitions.'
Then there is his worry about what Scotland will develop or import to
replace the current wave of high-technology industries that have
successfully replaced the old industrial economy of coal, shipbuilding and
steel. He envisages assembling a think tank to help to devise a plan.
Is Scottish Enterprise the answer to Scotland's economic worries? 'There
will be time to look back and see if this was a sensible idea, but not for
about two years,' he says.
</TEXT>
