<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Old county names may return to Welsh map
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MORETON, Welsh correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has rejected calls for an elected assembly for Wales as part
of proposed local-government reform in the principality - and opted instead
for a reorganisation bringing back many of the old county names.
The assembly idea, which is supported by the Labour party, has been rejected
by Mr Nicholas Bennett, the Welsh Office junior minister with responsibility
for local-government matters.
Instead, the government is proposing to reorganise the eight counties and 37
districts into 19 unitary authorities.
Under the proposals, some old county names such as Pembrokeshire,
Breconshire and Anglesey will return.
The Welsh county and district authorities agree on the need for single-tier
authorities to replace the present two, but there is little common ground on
which tier should be the foundation of the new structure. At a meeting last
month with Mr David Hunt, the Welsh secretary, each proposed the abolition
of the other.
Mr Hunt is now suggesting that the capital, Cardiff, and the three main
towns - Swansea, Newport and Wrexham - should in effect revert to their
status before the 1974 reorganisation.
He is also proposing that the vast county of Powys, which covers the whole
of largely rural mid Wales, should be covered by six authorities.
In the north, Gwynedd would be abolished, with Anglesey reverting to its
pre-1974 position and the remainder called Caernarfon. Clwyd would remain as
a name, but it would lose Wrexham.
The present county of Mid Glamorgan would remain as a unit, but it would
lose Merthyr Tydfil, which would revert to its pre-1974 borough status.
In the west, Dyfed would be abolished, part going to form Ceredigion and the
rest returning to the old names Pembrokeshire and Carmarthenshire.
Mr Hunt is to hold meetings with the local authorities in the next few weeks
and further fine tuning is possible.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
