<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Council Elections: Liberal Democrats prove capacity to
surprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIBERAL Democrats proved once again last night their capacity to
surprise by out-performing the party's national opinion poll rating and
confounding gloomy predictions about its local election campaign.
As results came in last night, Liberal Democrat strategists sipped champagne
and rapidly revised projections of net losses for the party on seats it won
in 1987. Party officials congratulated themselves on making substantial net
gains after a campaign dominated by clashes on national issues between
Labour and the Conservatives.
Projections based on early results suggested the Liberal Democrats were
winning, perhaps, more than 20 per cent of the vote - compared with recent
opinion polls putting the party on about 14 or 15 per cent. Early this
morning the party was exceeding Labour in terms of net gains of seats.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, was able to claim vindication for
his strategy of concentrating efforts and resources in target areas -
notably Gosport, Hampshire, and Eastbourne, East Sussex, where the party
notched early victories. He was also able to claim, with some justification,
that in large areas of southern England, the Liberal Democrats, were the
only challengers to the Tories.
By taking control of - among others - Lewes in East Sussex, North Wiltshire,
North Devon, and Torbay in Devon the party more than fulfilled its promise
to increase its 'power and influence' where it already had a strong base.
'The Liberal Democrats are the clear winners tonight,' Mr Ashdown said.
'Where the Tories have to be beaten the Liberal Democrats are the clear and
powerful challengers.'
The party's campaign was deliberately different to Labour and the Tories,
concentrating on local issues and the party's strength at 'grassroots'
politics. The results further cemented the bonds between the old Liberal
party and the Social Democrat party which formed the Liberal Democrats after
the last general election.
Last year's local election results, where the party won about 16 per cent of
the vote, encouraged hopes that the damaging rifts at the time the merger
had been overcome.
The Eastbourne by-election, followed soon after by success in Ribble Valley,
brought further cheer. Last night's results suggest that period can be
relegated to the history books.
They will also encourage Mr Ashdown in his strategy of looking for a gradual
strengthening in his party's standing - rather than hoping for a frothy dash
for growth. Officials said the party had also made impressive gains in areas
of the country where it had not focused efforts.
What the Liberal Democrat party still has to prove is that it can displace
Labour as the main challenger to the Tories in more than a handful of seats
in the midlands and north England.
</TEXT>
