<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Council Elections: Left-wing rebels win five Liverpool seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEFT-WING labour rebels standing against official Labour candidates took
five out of six seats in the Liverpool council elections.
The six were either retiring Labour councillors already suspended from the
party or local nominees opposed to Liverpool's moderate Labour leadership.
The moderates were standing against the background of a series of strikes
aimed at stopping 1,000 redundancies among council workers. They
nevertheless improved their grip on the council with a gain from the Liberal
Democrats, the defeat of one of the rebels and the replacement of another in
a ward that remained loyal.
The rebels, their nominators and supporters now face expulsion from the
Labour Party. A report will be ready next week for submission to the May
meeting of Labour's national executive committee. Up to 100 people are
expected to be named.
Labour may also challenge the results in the election court, which can
disqualify winners if misconduct can be proved. Officials said early today
they had clear evidence of rebels misrepresenting themselves as official
candidates and confusing voters.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
