<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Food supply for 1m in Ethiopia enough for just 10 days
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN, Africa Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOOD STOCKS for over 1m people in Ethiopia will be exhausted in ten days,
the British charity Oxfam said yesterday, warning that without fresh
supplies the country's death toll would exceed the 1984 famine, Michael
Holman, Africa Editor writes.
'What I have seen has shaken me. It is even worse than I expected. The
suffering is already acute,' said Mr Frank Judd, Oxfam director who is on a
fact finding mission to Ethiopia, where civil wars threaten the government
of President Haile Mariam Mengistu.
'The dying could soon overshadow that of 1984 unless action is taken
immediately. The priorities are obvious: food, transport, water, medical
supplies and shelter.' Around 1m Ethiopians are estimated to have died in
the 1984-85 famine.
Accusing leading donors of 'dragging their feet', an Oxfam statement said
that only half the total food needs of Ethiopia for the year has been
pledged, and much less than that have been delivered by the main donors.
The European Community was still debating ways to fund 400,000 tonnes of
food aid which had been agreed to in principle 'more than two weeks ago',
said the charity.
In the west of the country there is only 14 days' food left for 300,000
refugees from Sudan, and in the northern Ogaden region, at least 500,000
Somali refugees have only 14 days supply left.
A further 200,000 Ethiopians who have returned from Ethiopia are also facing
'severe shortages', while relief efforts for 380,000 drought victims in
southern Ogaden are 'severely hampered by appalling road conditions.'
In the region of north Omo, 400,000 people 'are facing starvation' due to
crop failure, and the number is expected to almost double, says Oxfam.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1692</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / PM mediates pay deal to clear way for Australian port reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA'S waterfront reform programme appeared to be back on course
yesterday after employers and unions ended a pay dispute following all-night
negotiations chaired by Mr Bob Hawke, the prime minister.
Mr Hawke emerged from nearly 18 hours of non-stop talks in Sydney to
announce a deal which could clear the way for changes in manning
requirements and work practices in ports around Australia.
The deal must be ratified by the waterfront employers' association, the
Waterside Workers' Federation, the main dockside union, and the Industrial
Relations Commission, the national labour court.
However, it represents a significant political victory for Mr Hawke, who has
made waterfront reform a key element in a wider programme of structural
reform of the economy.
The prime minister intervened in the dispute after the Australian Council of
Trade Unions (ACTU) blocked waterfront reform in protest at a 2.5 per cent
ceiling on wage increases imposed across industry by the Commission.
The Commission's ruling conflicted with an earlier agreement between the
ACTU and the government, known as the Accord, under which workweek, plus
further productivity-backed payments and improved superannuation.
The deal reached yesterday excludes superannuation, but provides for most
other elements of the Accord, including the ADollars 12 payment. Waterfront
workers will also receive a further 6.12 per cent pay increase over two
years, provided reforms are agreed and implemented.
The unions agreed to ask the Commission to ratify the deal, removing
employers' fears that an agreement struck outside the framework of the
centralised wage fixing system could reduce their legal protection from
industrial disruption.
Mr Richard Setchell, managing director of Conaust, the biggest stevedoring
company, said the unions' agreement to deliver reform before receiving
productivity increases represented a significant breakthrough.
'They will get nothing, other than the ADollars 12, unless they come up with
the goods. That is a huge contrast with the past 50 years,' he said.
Mr Setchell said Conaust, a subsidiary of Peninsular and Oriental Steam
Navigation of the UK, hopes an agreement reducing its Sydney workforce by 30
per cent will be implemented next month.
Only one company has so far implemented an agreement under the reform
process, which the government says will reduce the waterfront workforce from
6,500 to 4,500 by September next year.
The ACTU, which voted on Wednesday to campaign for full payment of the
Accord, said the deal showed employers were willing to recognise that the
Commission's 2.5 per cent ceiling was unworkable.
'It is an indication of what is possible if employers are willing to sit
down and talk to us,' said Mr Martin Ferguson, ACTU president.
</TEXT>
