<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Delors urges democracy on Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DAKAR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, yesterday called on
African leaders to support democratic principles which he said could provide
an engine for change in developing countries.
Speaking to Senegal's national assembly in Dakar, Mr Delors said further
democratisation was essential if African countries were to meet the economic
challenges ahead.
Mr Delors is on his first visit as commission president to sub-Saharan
Africa.
Commission officials see the four-day trip as an opportunity to reaffirm the
links between the EC and Africa now that the potential for confrontation
between superpowers on the African continent is diminishing. The end of the
Cold War has also allowed leading donors such as the EC to link development
aid more explicitly to democratic and macro-economic improvements.
Like IMF and World Bank aid programmes, the EC's latest five-year Ecu12bn
(Pounds 8.34bn) aid package for African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) states
includes structural adjustment funds. That element of the programme, which
began last year, ties donations to economic developments in ACP countries.
But Mr Delors sought to distinguish the EC structural adjustment fund from
IMF and World Bank aid by stressing the human element of what he called the
'new conscience of development'. Economic initiatives such as privatisation
were important, he said, but they should not be pursued at the expense of
public services.
