<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Opposition to bank reform plan spreads
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER RIDDELL, US Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DOMESTIC and international opposition is growing to a US Treasury proposal
that foreign banks should put all their American activities into separately
capitalised local subsidiaries if they wish to engage in securities and
insurance operations.
This recommendation, in the Treasury's bank reform legislation, has already
been strongly criticised by international banking groups and by Mr Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Federal Reserve, who argue that it would
unnecessarily increase costs and could deter foreign banks from operating in
the US.
Until the last few days, the chances of such a proposal being approved
looked slim, in view of the desire of Democratic leaders of the House
banking committee for a narrowly-based bill focusing mainly on the
recapitalisation of the fund insuring bank deposits. But following lobbying
by Mr Nicholas Brady, treasury secretary, House Democrats have agreed to
consider the administration's wider-ranging proposals, including those
affecting foreign banks.
Sir Leon Brittan, vice president of the European Commission, this week
warned that the proposals would severely limit the ability of EC banks to
compete effectively in the US market. Foreign banks wishing to engage in
securities activities would have to convert their existing banking
operations from a branch or agency into a separately capitalised subsidiary.
They would have to conduct their activities on the basis of local US capital
rather the worldwide capital, as is now the case.
Mr Greenspan yesterday argued that the US 'sorely' needed to reform its
banking industry, but warned that bankers would 'make a big mistake if they
anticipate that modifications in laws and regulations alone will solve their
problems.'
He argued that to avoid a further credit crunch, bankers needed to raise
their capital ratios and lower their asset risks.
</TEXT>
