<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Lloyd's launches reforms in bid to reassure Names
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REFORMS designed to defuse tension at Lloyd's of London were announced
yesterday by the insurance market's authorities.
The changes aim to give more information to the 26,500 Names who back
underwriting with their personal wealth and to prevent disputes going to
court.
The measures come as the market faces the prospect of at least two years of
overall losses and as an increasing number of Names are resorting to the
courts to avert bankruptcy.
Mr Alan Lord, the Lloyd's chief executive, said the 'overall purpose of the
package is to reassure Names and ensure that the consequences of losses are
dealt with within the family of Lloyd's rather than in a public forum.'
Names should benefit from three separate measures:
A procedure to review 'major' insurance losses by any of the market's 354
syndicates is to be introduced next month.
Where a syndicate's net loss at the end of the market's three-year
accounting period amounts to 150 per cent or more of the syndicate's
allocated capacity - the amount of premium it is permitted to write
according to market regulations - the governing body of Lloyd's will review
the 'commercial circumstances' of the loss.
Committees, possibly comprising former Lloyd's underwriters and chaired by
an independent outsider, will conduct the reviews. Mr Lord said the reviews
would not be published but they would generally be made available to Names
via their members' agents.
Mr Lord insisted that the reviews would be 'quite distinct' from
investigations relating to matters of potential misconduct.
The investigation 'is not designed to point the finger at anyone', he said.
Conciliation and arbitration procedures will be revised in an attempt to
resolve disputes between members of Lloyd's and their agents before they go
to court. 'Before litigation there is a role for conciliation,' Mr Lord
said.
A conciliation scheme for settling disputes between Names and their agents
will be developed, while arbitration procedures, established in 1987, will
be streamlined to reduce delays.
Syndicates are to be obliged to disclose the salaries paid to underwriters
in published annual reports from 1990.
This follows criticism that the rise in Lloyd's underwriters' salaries - who
can expect to earn Pounds 75,000-Pounds 300,000 a year - has depressed
syndicates' profitability.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
