<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / World Stock Markets: Eastern Europe learns the symbolic
value of bourses - The progress towards capitalism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'In many communist countries, stock exchanges rank with McDonald's as icons
of capitalism. Establishment of a stock exchange, therefore, has symbolic
value and may lend credibility to government efforts towards economic
reform.'
Match that assertion with stretched limousines awaiting customers at Warsaw
airport and academic critiques on the Polish Road to Capitalism, and you can
get something of the feel of what is happening in eastern Europe, or at the
very least of what some (mainly western-based) entrepreneurs hope will
happen in the developing capital markets of the former communist countries.
The McDonald's analogy comes from a young, engaging and bright Italian
lawyer who took up residence a few weeks ago in Prague, 'because I like the
city'; presumably his bosses at the World Bank, in Washington, approved of
the location, not least because of its political sensitivity.
Mr Cesare Calari, a product of Bologna's Law School, picked up his
near-perfect English at the John Hopkins university in the US, won a
placement under the World Bank's Young Professionals Programme, and went to
work for the bank's affiliate, the International Finance Corporation (IFC).
Moving by way of responsibility and concern for central America, east Asia
and southern Africa, he is back not too far from his native Italy, in the
Czech capital of Prague. His job: the IFC's regional representative in
eastern Europe, capital markets division.
If stock markets take off in eastern Europe, some of the credit should go to
Mr Calari and his IFC colleagues. They are now laying the groundwork for the
emergence of capital markets in the former communist countries of the east,
designing the essential nuts and bolts for a lot of new capitalist
McDonald's, from Poland to Hungary, Yugoslavia to Czechoslovakia and Romania
and, in between, to Warsaw, Belgrade, Zegrab, Ljubjana and (a delicate task
from Prague) Bratislava, the Slovak capital.
'The current transition to market economies in eastern Europe is a task
whose scale, scope and complexity have few precedents in economic history,'
says Mr Calari.
'In addition, considerable emphasis has been placed on the development of
capital markets and their tangible expression: the stock exchanges. These
institutions must play a key role in the privatisation of state-owned
enterprises by providing liquidity for their shares.'
The task would be a formidable one, even on a clear playing field. But the
field is by no means clear; it risks getting overcrowded with players, not
always on the same side. Everyone wants to help eastern Europe along the
road to developed capital markets, but the motivation ranges from
exploitation to enlightened self-interest, from greed to genuine offers of
help.
The players include second and third-level financial intermediaries - many
out for a fast buck - as well as the World Bank and IFC, the International
Monetary Fund and Mr Jacques Attali's creation, the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development.
Then there is the Federation of Stock Exchanges in the European Community,
and its component parts; the French are helping the Poles to see the
capitalist light, while the Germans are giving a hand to the Czechs and
Hungarians. The Poles are also talking to the British and the Canadians, and
no one appears to be co-ordinating anything.
At a recent London conference on European Securities Markets in the 1990s,
Mr Calari agreed that there was a risk of confusion, conflicting advice,
exploitation and overkill, but was too modest to say whether the IFC was
best placed to take the lead role.
The work to be done is enormous. The political commitment appears to be
there, although varying from country to country, but there is not much else.
For all practical purposes, none of the east European countries has the
regulatory and legal framework necessary for the efficient conduct of
securities business, an essential assurance for western investors.
The concept of the joint stock company hardly exists, and there is an
appalling minefield (witness what is happening in the former East Germany)
over property rights and ownership.
Audited accounts do not exist; there is little or no corporate information
available for analysis; the business press is under-developed or scarred by
too many years of communist rule; there are infrastructural problems, even
down to market basics such as telephones and photocopying machines, to say
nothing of trading screens and computers, and there is little hard currency
with which to buy them.
Everyone is offering to help, and hoping to gain. But there is hard work to
be done, not just in establishing capital markets but also in educating
potential investors. No one should expect quick results.
</TEXT>
