<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Group sees growing silver
deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SILVER market is facing a growing deficit which could reach 100m ounces
this year, according to American Precious Metals Advisors, the consultancy
group.
This is contrary to a popular belief - based on faulty supply and demand
data - in a surplus for the market, which is suffering from weak prices and
growing warehouse stocks.
'Nothing is further from the truth,' says the group in a silver review. 'The
silver market in recent years has been in deficit: industrial and coinage
demand exceeds current supplies from mine production, scrap recovery and
government disposals.'
The review claims that most information on the silver market is wide of the
mark. For example, most analyses estimate that annual photographic
consumption in the past few years has been between 190m and 210m ounces.
This does not include consumption by film manufacturing plants in Mexico,
Brazil, Korea, Singapore, and Taiwan, it says.
Similarly, the newly industrialised countries' use of silver in the
electronics sector, the second biggest consumer of silver, is not properly
accounted for in generally accepted statistics.
In spite of the rapid growth of silver usage in the newly industrial
countries, the accepted view is that demand outside the US, Japan and
Western Europe has increased by only 10m ounces to 20m ounces since the
1970s, says the review.
'This is absolutely impossible: first, the industrialised nations have been
major importers of manufactured goods - manufactured goods with high silver
content - from these newly industrialised countries. Second, rising
prosperity in many of those countries has led to rapid growth in domestic
demand for silver-containing photographic film and electronic goods.'
The review says its own statistics should be seen as 'presenting a blurred
picture of reality', with total consumption, if anything understated, at
590m ounces. It puts total supply slightly down this year at 481m ounces.
The real problem of the silver market is that investors, particularly in the
US, 'no longer wish to hold silver that has been accumulated and hoarded for
years if not decades.
'The declining price of silver reflects a continuing desire on the part of
investors to reduce their portfolio holdings, But, each year, aggregate
silver holdings can decline by no more than the annual deficit.'
This disinvestment, which will be able to satisfy substantial market
deficits for years to come, explains the declining price and the build-up in
visible warehouse stocks.
'Given this situation, the only thing that will force silver prices higher
during the next year is a change in investor and speculator sentiment
towards silver,' the review says. While long term hoarders are abandoning
silver, the market action will be dominated by the behaviour of traders and
speculators.
METALS Fax, weekly. Dollars 6,000 a year from APMA, 3034 NW 61st Street,
Boca Raton, Florida 33496.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
