<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / The Property Market: Gloom still overwhelms signs of hope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HAS the property market hit the bottom? As economic confidence starts to
creep back, some of the optimists in the property industry are calling the
turn. 'All indicators now point to the bottom of the market having been
reached, with the time ripe for institutional investment,' says Edward
Erdman, the chartered surveyor.
Signs of a revival in confidence are plentiful, if tentative. Property is
now so cheap in relation to gilts, that hitherto bearish commentators are
recommending that institutions increase their holdings. In fact, yields have
risen so far that property is virtually being valued as a fixed-income
asset. That has fuelled buying interest from companies and individuals, such
as Alan Sugar who sold Pounds 34m of Amstrad shares to go back into the
property market.
Continental investors, attracted by the reduced currency risk from the UK's
entry into the Exchange Rate Mechanism are also showing interest. And after
two desperately quiet years, cautious buyers have re-emerged for property
unit trusts.
Appearances, however, may deceive. While certain parts of the property
market may have hit bottom, it is far from being a broadly-based recovery.
'Thinly disguised untruths about imminent recovery are very foolish,'
comments Mr Rupert Nabarro of Investment Property Databank, which has just
conducted an annual review into the investment property market. Moreover,
the share market, which has proved a reliable guide to future events, has
just pushed property shares relative to the rest of the market to a 22-year
low.
The reason for caution lies in the divergence between the investment market
and the occupiers' market, which has been ravaged by the recession. Concern
is focused on the unprecedented problems in the central London office
market.
Thanks to the overbuilding that followed the deregulation of planning
controls and the over-expansion of the financial services industry after Big
Bang in 1986, London's office vacancy rate far outstrips the 11 per cent
experienced after the 1974 collapse. 'The figures are by any standards -
absolute, historical or whatever - awful and imply a collapse in rents in
central London,' says Chris Walls of Salomon Brothers.
After the 1974 crash, rents fell by 40 per cent from their peak. This time,
in Salomon's view, the fall could be just as severe. Some brokers think even
this is too optimistic. One believes that rents could fall 60 per cent from
their peak.
The result is that capital values will probably fall, even if yields
partially recover. And a partial recovery is expected even by the bears at
Salomon. 'Unfortunately, there is rarely much (if any) correlation between
the property market and logic,' says Chris Walls. 'As interest rates fall,
the pressure on short-term market operators will ease, and they will no
longer find it so urgent to sell at current yield levels.'
Another reason for expecting yields to fall is that turnover in much of the
market has virtually ground to a halt, thanks to the mismatch between
buyers' and sellers' expectations.
Once prices do improve, however, the supply of property may vastly increase
as institutions and companies resume the rationalisation of their portfolios
and banks push more companies into receivership. If so, it is not clear
where the demand will come from.
 ------------------------------------------------------------------
Rental Growth (%)
 ------------------------------------------------------------------
                    Retail   Office   Industrial   All Properties
 ------------------------------------------------------------------
Year to March 91     3.2      0.5        4.9           2.5
Quarter to March 91  0.2     -1.2        0.5          -0.3
Month of March 91    0.0     -0.3        0.1          -0.1
