FT  03 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Canada's oil and gas M&amp;A
activity rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE PACE of mergers and acquisitions in Canada's oil and gas industry soared
to a record in the first three months of this year.
Sayer Securities of Calgary reported that 222 deals, valued at CDollars 910m
(Dollars 791.30m) were signed in the first quarter, compared with 174 in the
previous three months.
The biggest transaction was Gulf Canada's CDollars 100m sale of its working
interest in the Caroline natural gas field in Alberta to Shell Canada. Sayer
estimates that assets and companies worth CDollars 3.6bn were still up for
sale at the end of March, down from CDollars 4.1bn three months earlier.
Since then, however, Olympia &amp; York, the real estate and natural resources
group controlled by Toronto's Reichmann family, has disclosed that it has
received offers for its controlling interest in Home Oil of Calgary.
Amoco Canada Petroleum has also announced plans for a further
reorganisation. On the other hand, PanCanadian Petroleum, the energy arm of
Canadian Pacific, has expressed interest in making a sizeable acquisition.
Merger and takeover activity in Canada's oil and gas industry has been at a
high pitch for the past three or four years. The main sellers have been
companies such as Esso Resources, Amoco, Gulf Canada and Petro-Canada.
The most active buyers have included fast-growing companies, such as Chauvco
Resources, Inverness Petroleum and Poco Petroleums.
