<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Bonds: Cheaper rates encourage three Canadian
issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE Canadian dollar Eurobonds were launched in the international capital
markets yesterday as European investors returned after Wednesday's May Day
holiday.
The Eurobond market is now offering cheaper rates than the domestic market,
even for Canadian borrowers which have historically found the domestic
market a cheaper source of funds.
The domestic market suffered a setback this week when the Province of
Ontario's triple-A rated debt was placed under review for possible
downgrading by Standard &amp; Poor's, following a disappointing budget.
Ontario's debt provides a pricing benchmark for much of the domestic market,
so spreads over the government bond market widened 6 or 7 basis points.
Eurobond spreads also widened, but soon recovered.
The largest deal of the day was a CDollars 250m three-year deal for the
Province of Saskatchewan, considered attractively priced at a 75 basis point
margin above the comparable Canadian government bond. Placement was split
between institutional and retail investors in Europe, according to lead
manager Wood Gundy.
While other Canadian provinces have been frequent visitors to the Eurobond
market this year, reflecting both increased borrowing needs and improved
European demand, single-A rated Saskatchewan had until now found the
domestic market a cheaper source of funds.
The Canadian municipality of Hamilton tapped the market with a CDollars 75m
issue of retractable notes, a structure usually reserved for the domestic
market. The 15-year deal, puttable after five and 10-years, is targetted at
institutional investors.
Also in the Canadian dollar sector, Petrofina, the Belgian oil company,
launched a CDollars 100m issue, which met firm demand among yield-hungry
investors in Benelux. Petrofina is Belgium's largest company, but its lack
of credit rating tends to deter investors elsewhere. The company is
currently seeking a rating.
In Germany, Nichii, the Japanese department store chain, launched the
largest ever D-mark equity-linked deal for a Japanese borrower. The DM500m
four-year deal was quoted below its par issue price at 99 1/2 offered.
Japanese equity warrant deals are normally expected to trade above their
issue price in the primary market.
A Pounds 100m four-year deal for the Nationwide Anglia Building Society via
Baring Brothers was considered aggressively priced, at a yield spread of 81
basis points above the 10 1/4 per cent gilt due 1995. However, lead manager
Baring Brothers pointed out that other paper at that area of the yield curve
was trading substantially over par, which deters many investors.
</TEXT>
