<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Capital Markets: Securities clearing plan on
course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST of the clearing and settlement systems supporting the world's biggest
securities markets are still on course to meet internationally agreed
standards of performance by the end of next year, according to a report*
from the Group of Thirty.
However, a number of countries - including the UK, Spain, Italy, Australia
and Hong Kong - face substantial developments if they are not to fall
farther behind. Within Europe particularly, the efficiency and security of
settlement arrangements have become an important aspect of the competition
between national exchanges.
G30, an international group of financial and economic experts chaired by
Lord Richardson, a former governor of the Bank of England, laid down a
series of recommended standards in 1989.
These include the creation of central securities depositories, delivery
versus payment mechanisms (to ensure cash and securities change hands
simultaneously) and rolling settlement, with all transactions being settled
three days after the trade date. The deadline set for most targets is the
end of next year.
A series of progress reports from 21 countries, published by G30 this week,
show that most expect to be able to reach the targets on time. In an
introduction to the report, Lord Richardson paid tribute to what he called
'impressive' efforts, given the 'substantial investment' called for at a
difficult time for the industry, and the fact that many changes would result
in upheavals in working practice.
Some of the most developed settlement systems still lack key elements, Lord
Richardson said. These include those in Japan, which is about to start
loading information onto its central depository, France, which has yet to
move to rolling settlement, and the US, which faces considerable opposition
from the retail market in moving to three-day rolling settlement.
Greater difficulties face countries like the UK, he added. 'With a
paper-based system, no comprehensive central depository, no rolling
settlement and no satisfactory delivery versus payment, the UK has a long
and difficult hill to climb.'
* Clearance and Settlement Systems Status Reports: Year-end 1990, Group of
Thirty. Dollars 50/Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
