<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: DSM earnings dip to Fl 178m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DER KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DSM, the Dutch chemicals group, yesterday said net profit fell by 26.4 per
cent to Fl 178m (Dollars 93.7m) in the first quarter of 1991 compared with
the same period last year.
If extraordinary items are excluded from both years, net profit was down
19.1 per cent at Fl 182m, roughly unchanged from the lower final quarter of
1990.
In 1990, DSM posted a 22 per cent decline in net profit excluding
extraordinary items and a 38 per cent drop including these items.
Sales were down 11 per cent at Fl 2.6bn in the 1991 quarter, with most of
the decline attributed to DSM's decision in 1990 to deconsolidate the
results of Macintosh, its 56 per cent-owned retail group.
Selling prices rose an average of 3 per cent, but this was more than offset
by a 5 per cent decline in sales volume, particularly in basic chemicals.
DSM said first-quarter results were also affected by the start-up costs of
new production facilities.
Like other Dutch companies, DSM said it was unable to predict 1991 results
because of the economic uncertainties prevailing on a number of its key
markets.
</TEXT>
