   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LURGI, the engineering subsidiary of Germany's Metallgesellschaft group,
plans to float a minority stake in its environmental company later this year
to help finance clean-up operations in east and west Germany.
This will mark a further step in a series of deals involving
Metallgesellschaft. Recent moves have included its acquisition from Davy
Corporation of the UK of Zimmer, the German industrial plant builder which
now comes under Lurgi, and Daimler-Benz's acquisition of a 10 per cent stake
in Metallgesellschaft.
The stock market flotation of the unit,
Lurgi-Umwelt-Beteiligungsgesellschaft(LUB) will be the second 'green' share
issue by the group. Last year, a minority of Metallgesellschaft's recycling
subsidiary, Berzelius Umwelt-Service (BUS), was floated in Frankfurt to
raise DM220m (Dollars 124m)
Mr Jens-Peter Schaefer, Lurgi's chief executive, said it hoped to raise a
similar sum for LUB.
The money would help finance initial investments in the environmental
sector; these would probably be higher than at BUS, since the scope of the
clean-up task on the ground was enormous.
