<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / International Company News: Siemens close to French deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SIEMENS NIXDORF, the German computer group, is in the final phase of
negotiating a technical and industrial agreement with SMT-Goupil, France's
last remaining independent maker of microcomputers.
The talks come as SMT-Goupil, the subject of a management buy-out four years
ago, is suffering heavy losses due to the fall in demand and prices that has
crippled the computer industry generally.
Trading in SMT-Goupil's shares was suspended last month, just before it
issued an estimate that it lost 'several hundred million francs' last year
on turnover of around FFr830m (Dollars 139m).
SMT-Goupil was barely profitable in the previous year, with a FFr30m net
surplus on sales of FFr1.8bn.
Neither side will confirm nor deny French press reports that Siemens Nixdorf
is poised to take a 20 per cent stake in SMT-Goupil, though a spokesman for
Siemens Nixdorf yesterday stressed that the German company 'is not
contemplating any involvement in putting SMT-Goupil back on its feet'.
The pair were discussing 'technical and industrial agreements within the
normal scope of business between European industrial companies,' he said.
Whatever the final outcome, this looks set to mark a new foreign advance in
a French computer industry which used to be seen as a strategic national
preserve. Loss-making Bull, France's state-owned computer group, is now
negotiating for NEC, the Japanese electronics group, to take up to 5 per
cent of the group's capital in exchange for NEC's existing 15 per cent stake
in Bull HN, its main overseas subsidiary.
Bull last year boosted the size of its microcomputer business by taking over
Zenith Data Systems of the US, part of Bull's diversification away from its
traditional mainframes business, but which also had the side-effect of
increasing the pressure on smaller microcomputer makers like SMT-Goupil.
Siemens itself bought a controlling stake only two years ago in IN2, a
French producer of IBM-compatible personal computers, from the
Intertechnique electronics group.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
