<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Computing the need for a byte into staffing
levels - IBM UK's radical re-organisation, forced on the company by
recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK subsidiary of International Business Machines (IBM), the world's
largest computer manufacturer, is implementing a radical re-organisation
which will fundamentally affect the way the company does business in Britain
and result in the likely loss of some 1,000 staff between now and 1993.
The shake-up in UK operations is described by Mr Nick Temple, IBM UK's
general manager, as the broadest the company has ever attempted. Indeed it
goes beyond 1989's worldwide re-organisation to combat sluggish sales and
declining profits. That initiative resulted in the elimination of thousands
of jobs and several layers of bureaucracy.
The new measures have been forced on the company by the recession in the UK
which has slowed growth drastically and exposed IBM's comparative
inflexibility and lack of competitiveness.
Last week it announced a rationalisation in its manufacturing activities,
involving the loss of 400 jobs over three years, to improve competitiveness
and its chances of bringing new manufacturing commissions to the UK. IBM
manufacturing units compete with each other in its three principal markets -
the US, Europe and Asia - to win manufacturing 'missions'.
IBM UK's financial performance last year was significantly poorer than the
company as a whole. Revenues grew to Pounds 4.3bn, up only 3 per cent, while
pre-tax profits fell to Pounds 420m (Pounds 459m) in the second year of
declining profitability. Mr Temple believes profits will be either flat or
reduced in the UK this year.
By comparison, the IBM group worldwide turned over Dollars 69bn in 1990, a
10 per cent rise, and pre-tax profits rose 54 per cent to Dollars 10.2bn.
Earlier this year, moreover, IBM intrigued Europe's personal computer
industry by appointing Mr William McCracken as general manager for personal
systems (personal computers) in Europe, only a few months after
responsibility for personal systems throughout the region had been given to
Mr Tony Cleaver, UK chairman and chief executive. Mr McCracken is based at
IBM's European headquarters in Paris. IBM explains the move as a
re-organisation made necessary by the fast-changing nature of the personal
computer business.
Mr Cleaver, Sir Leonard Peach, director of personnel and corporate affairs,
and Mr JB Holmes, director of manufacturing, were involved in the
preparation of the recovery plan, although its overall shape was the
responsibility of Mr Temple, appointed general manager in December last
year. This week Mr Temple denied that his authorship of the plan reflected
any change of emphasis at the top of the company, explaining that Mr
Cleaver's role was focused on IBM UK's external relationships.
Mr Temple has been briefing IBM's top managers on the scheme over the past
few days and they have been filtering the details to the company's 18,000 UK
employees.
Senior management from Armonk, IBM's world headquarters in New York State,
are taking a keen interest in the development of the scheme. IBM now derives
more of its profits from Europe than from the US. The recession in the UK,
however, has proved an early indicator of slowing growth in Europe. The UK
is seen in Armonk, it seems, as a test case of how to deal with a European
market in recession.
The plan has six elements:
An increase of about 600 to 6,300 in the company's direct salesforce with
the objective of bringing more salespeople in touch with customers. Mr
Temple said the number of people involved in buying decisions had multiplied
as information technology spread through companies and the extra salespeople
would be necessary to maintain more comprehensive contacts with customers.
A 20 per cent improvement in the effectiveness of the UK salesforce. Mr
Temple said this would not be measured in extra sales, but would involve
finding ways for salespeople and support staff to spend more time with
customers through the elimination of bureaucracy. He was anxious to improve
speed of response and quality of service via the reduction of management
layers from the present six or seven to five.
A new emphasis on market specialisation. In the past, IBM has presented
itself as a general purpose computer company, willing to tackle any
customer's data processing problem. With increased competition from small,
fast-moving niche market specialists, that approach is no longer viable.
Local government and the public sector were among the areas where IBM
intended to concentrate its efforts. He would not say where the company
intended to back-pedal.
An increased concentration on computing services, the fastest-growing area
of the computer industry. This includes not only computer software but also
facilities management - where the company runs a computer centre on behalf
of a customer - systems integration and information technology consultancy.
There are 400 staff on the computing services side at present; the idea is
to increase that number to 2,000 through redeployment of existing staff.
Reorganisation of the products side of the company into a number of business
units, self-contained in their operations, but not independent of the rest
of the company. There will be product business units dealing with, for
example, mainframes, mid-range systems and with the company's open systems
products which use IBM's AIX operating system.
An experiment which has turned the branch at Richmond, London, into a field
business unit functioning as a profit centre rather than a revenue centre is
to be extended to the rest of the country. Some 30-40 business units are to
be established by the end of the year.
A new emphasis on selling to small businesses through the addition of a
commercial sector to IBM's traditional marketing areas of manufacturing
industry, banking and finance, and government.
</TEXT>
