<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / UK Company News: Tace faces fresh clash over choice of
chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSTITUTIONAL investors are today expected to reopen a campaign to place
their own choice of chairman on the board of Tace, the environmental control
group whose founder, Mr Jock Mackenzie, they ousted last year.
The moves came as shares in the stock rose 12p to 162p in active trading
amid speculation that Mr Bob Morton, the City financier, may be stalking
Tace through Southwind which holds a 4.4 per cent stake.
The institutions, led by Framlington - with a 16 per cent stake - and
Norwich Union - with 5 per cent - are understood to remain deeply
unsatisfied with Sir David Nicolson, who replaced Mr Mackenzie as chairman.
They had favoured Mr Michael Beckett, who joined the board as a director but
quit without explanation last week on the same day that Hoare Govett
resigned as the company's brokers.
The institutions are anxious that a financial restructuring that was
hurriedly announced last Friday should not take place before a full
independent audit into the company's activities and management has been
carried out.
Mr Beckett was also understood to be pushing for the audit. His departure is
thought to have triggered Hoare Govett's after only three weeks as the
company's broker.
It was not clear whether the institutions would be demanding that Mr Beckett
be installed as chairman. Before his resignation he was accused of working
too closely with the institutions and with trying to install his own people.
Sir David said that if he was going to be chairman he would have to be
allowed to run the company without constant interference.
The revolt appears to demonstrate an increasing willingness by institutions
to flex muscles in what they see as cases of poor corporate governance. The
Tace move comes only a day after the removal of Mr John Fletcher, the
chairman of Budgens, following pressure from Electra, IEP and Gartmore.
The proposed capital reorganisation involves Tace buying the 49 per cent of
Goring Kerr, the process control equipment affiliate, which it currently
does not control. It would also involve a rights issue.
Tace said the restructuring would cut overheads and lead to significant tax
savings and improved synergy between the two companies.
Mr Steve Walton, the Tace company secretary, said yesterday that there had
been no discussions with Mr Morton and that there was no sign that Southwind
was behind yesterday's active share dealing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
