<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Letter: The coalition that will realise a goal of Indian
decentralisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PRITAM SINGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Joe Rogaly's excellent article, 'Passage to India' (April 23), and
David Housego's two field reports from Kashmir (April 22 and 24) highlight
very vividly the problems of over-centralisation in India. Two points,
however, need further elaboration.
First, that the resistance to the centralised Indian state does not come
only from states like Kashmir, Punjab and Nagaland/Mizoram, where Moslems,
Sikhs and Christians respectively are in a minority, but also from many
Hindu-majority states in the non-Hindi-speaking regions like Assam (for
secession), Orissa (the chief minister there threatened secession), Andhra
Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Kerala, Karnataka and West Bengal (for greater
autonomy). This phenomenon is a manifestation of the conflict between many
nationalisms in India and a unified Hindi-dominated Indian nationalism
articulated by the Indian centralist state. These non-Hindi nationalist
movements, having remained dormant during the struggle for Indian
independence, are now reasserting their identities. Mr Rogaly's suggestion
that Indians, in order to 'realise their potential', need to not only move
towards confederation but also 'risk that in the end some of them go their
separate ways' is, indeed, very full of insight and bold.
Second, Rajiv Gandhi's coming to power - which in Mr Rogaly's opinion may be
the probable outcome of this month's general election - will not lead to
decentralisation of power because Mr Gandhi's Congress party, reared in the
Nehru political culture of centralisation, is programmatically opposed to
decentralisation. Only a long-term defeat of the Congress by a coalition of
parties representing different nationalisms can possibly realise the goal of
decentralisation.
Pritam Singh,
Oriel College,
Oxford
</TEXT>
