<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Letter: Non-executive directors and their role in corporate
governance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr ALLEN SYKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The recent report of the Institutional Shareholders Committee on the
best practice in the role and duties of directors ('Code urges separation of
company boards' top roles', April 19) is a curious and disappointing paper.
A statement of best practice on an important topic is useful when such
practice represents a satisfactory solution to the problem. When, however,
the best practice cannot begin to remedy the much-publicised basic
weaknesses in British corporate governance, such a paper is particularly
unsatisfactory.
For over two years an important debate has been continuing on the
inadequacies of British corporate governance, most notably in your paper and
The Economist. It has covered the related subjects of short-termism,
excessive takeover activity and absentee shareholders. Much analysis has
occurred and many remedies have been proposed. All this is ignored by the
committee's paper.
Your writers, Richard Waters (April 19) and Barry Riley (April 20) have
already commented penetratingly on some of the paper's paradoxes, and
particularly the shuffling of all responsibility for better corporate
governance on to the already overloaded shoulders of non-executive
directors. (The committee expects to put the burden entirely on such
directors while taking no part in choosing and nominating them]) The
committee only sees them as a combination of nanny and policeman, but at
most this should be a subsidiary role. The best non-executive directors can
make their contribution by helping businesses to expand profitably - their
main role in western Europe. Accordingly, they deserve profit-based
incentives as well as executive directors.
The most serious weakness in British corporate governance is the lack of
committed, knowledgeable long-term owners. The institutions are unwilling to
fulfil this role, preferring the right to chop and change investment
positions at will. It leaves a vacuum in corporate governance no other
entities can fill. This is the prime cause of short-termism. It has reduced
long term corporate returns in Britain below west European levels, and far
below Japanese levels, yet without benefiting the average institution. Their
returns, as Barry Riley reminds us, are lower even than average corporate
returns. Everyone loses.
In sum, we have a system of corporate governance, ownership and finance
inferior to our main European and Far East rivals. Investment institutions
must accept their responsibility for this, and join with industry in finding
effective remedies.
We need fewer institutional shareholders per company, and a knowledgeable
long-term commitment from them. Then, as in western Europe they should
participate in appointing effective, well remunerated non-executive
directors whose main role would be to help companies run profitably. Perhaps
the Institutional Shareholders Committee would address these more relevant
issues in a further paper.
Allen Sykes,
Mallington,
29 The Mount,
Fetcham,
Leatherhead, Surrey
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
