<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Letter: No benign feelings in the present recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr D B ROBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, When, a decade ago, the recession, which particularly hit the building
industry, brought us to our knees, we had no feeling of resentment against
the government. We recognised that draconian measures were necessary to curb
inflation and to alter radically the habits of many years of socialism and
quasi-socialism. It nevertheless took us six years to recover from the
destruction of our infrastructure brought about by that recession.
This time round, we have no such benign feelings towards the government. We
regard the recession as being the result of unforgivable incompetence by the
government.
We have listened with anger to government spokesmen calling for investment
by industry in innovation. What industry is suffering from now is lack of
liquidity resulting from its having made plans for innovation and expansion
when interest rates were in the 7-10 per cent band. Even those rates were
high, but, in the belief then that government could maintain a reasonable
degree of economic stability, the plans were perfectly prudent.
It is not just that by doubling interest rates the cost of borrowing was
doubled, and, more importantly, that even one's most pessimistic sales
forecasts were undermined. What gives us cause for anger is that the
government was clearly unaware of what it was doing and the effect it would
have. Even as late as after Christmas the prime minister was telling us that
there was no recession. When finally he conceded that it existed, it was
described as being 'shallow and short-lived'.
How can industry be expected to plan in the light of such lack of
understanding by government of what constitutes a workable economic
framework?
The Conservatives would now have us believe that, having re-vamped local
government taxation, they are set fair to win another election. I can only
say that I feel disenfranchised. I want no repeat of the socialist
experience, but have lost faith in the government. Indeed, I feel now as I
did when Mr Heath was in power - the Conservatives need a term in
opposition, during which they can do some re-thinking.
D B Robb,
managing director,
Marlborough Ceramic Tiles,
Elcot Lane,
Marlborough,
Wiltshire
</TEXT>
