<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Arts: Toronto Symphony Orchestra - Barbican Hall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
So many visiting orchestras have brought us Brahms symphonies recently. It
hardly seems worth an orchestra crossing the Atlantic to give us another,
but the Toronto Symphony Orchestra is not the kind to make the journey for
nothing, to judge from this determined showing.
The orchestra's tour has taken in London and Glasgow. At the Barbican on
Wednesday it offered what might have looked a dour programme. A new work by
Raymond Luedeke and Bartok's Viola Concerto did not exactly make a festive
start for a concert in the presence of royalty. But there were compensations
and it is not meant as a slight on the orchestra to say that the outstanding
feature up until the interval was the playing of the soloist, Yury Bashmet.
The Bartok concerto is a late piece, which refuses to give up its true
feelings easily in what seems a hostile musical environment. Bashmet played
it supremely well, not only making sure that the viola was always the prime
mover in the orchestral texture, but also voicing his part with a marvellous
freedom and spontaneity. The opening of the slow movement can rarely have
been so hauntingly sad.
This was the 'difficult' modern music on the programme, not the Luedeke. The
North Wind's Gift is an orchestral piece lasting about 10 minutes, the token
example of new work from its own country that many a visiting orchestra
brings, well crafted, but quite unmemorable as to its content. The music
felt like the accompaniment to something more important and it was no
surprise to read that it is taken from an opera in progress.
And so to Brahms's First Symphony. Gunther Herbig has been Music Director in
Toronto more or less since Andrew Davis left in 1988 and he is evidently
shaping his orchestra into a fine vehicle for the German classics. The
Toronto players gave us Brahms with none of the spurious heaviness of the
Oslo Philharmonic a few weeks ago; they made wind and brass parts engage
with a vigour missed by the Leipzig Gewandhaus last autumn.
Everything was well balanced, purposeful, warm enough in sound. For his part
Herbig did nothing untoward or exaggerated, but brought to a central,
Germanic style of performance just the combination of urgency and passion
that so miserably eluded Giulini recently in the Festival Hall. This was a
Brahms First Symphony some way above the average. Well worth the journey, in
fact.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
</DOC>
