FT  03 MAY 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Though Friday is not the best night for the enthusiastic viewer, this
evening's early movie on BBC2 is a good one: The Crimson Pirate (6.00). The
word 'swashbuckling' might have been invented for it. Burt Lancaster employs
all the skills mastered in his early career as a circus acrobat, and
delivers lines such as 'I'll fly my flag into the mouths of their cannon and
if you've crimson in your veins you'll follow me' with that clenched teeth
grin that became his trademark.
Then ITV begins a new sitcom called Second Thoughts (8.00) which may be
good, you never know; it does have former Likely Lad James Bolam in it and
also Lynda Bellingham. However, we are told 'Divorcees Bill and Faith are
moving in together but her teenage children and his ex wife are not making
it easy'. Perhaps that makes your heart skip. It makes mine sink.
The Chief (9.00 ITV) sustains a fairly impressive standard of production,
even if it is not the most subtle or surprising police series. The plot is
now much concerned with 'community policing' and in today's story Stafford
appeals to the residents of a rundown estate for help in catching those who
have killed a police officer.
