<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Management (Corporate Strategy): ICI goes native in the land
of the long-term - The UK group's investment in Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Almost every day, it seems, one Japanese company or another announces that
it is setting up a factory or development centre in Europe or America.
Although the reverse process has had less publicity, western companies are
in fact pouring many billions of yen into new manufacturing and research
facilities in Japan.
One of the most striking examples is ICI, Britain's largest manufacturer.
ICI was slower to move into Japan than other international chemicals groups;
four years ago its Japanese activities were limited to importing chemicals
and participating in joint ventures with local companies.
Today, after a Pounds 100m investment spree, ICI is the 100 per cent owner
of two new factories (one making polyester film and the other
pharmaceuticals) and two research centres (one for specialist chemicals and
new materials and the other for agrochemicals).
Land, labour and materials are so expensive in Japan that these investments
will not pay for themselves for several years. The ICI board accepted that
the Pounds 50m plant to produce Melinex polyester film, opened last October,
would give a significantly lower rate of return, looked at in isolation,
than adding to existing production capacity in Europe or the US.
But the strategy being pursued by ICI is not just about selling more goods
in Japan. It is also - and perhaps more importantly - about hitching its
fortunes firmly to the global expansion of Japan's end-user industries,
especially automobiles and electronics.
Only by doing research and manufacturing in Japan can ICI effectively
develop special chemicals and materials in collaboration with the giant car
companies such as Toyota and Honda and electronics companies such as
Matsushita and Sony. The idea is that ICI will then be able to sell these
products to Japanese-owned car and electronics plants around the world - and
at the same time will gain competitive advantage in selling similar products
to the remaining European and American car and electronics manufacturers.
Japanese companies prefer to collaborate with chemicals suppliers which have
scientists and engineers in Japan and a factory to produce material locally.
For example, ICI has already lost the strong position it had 10 years ago as
a supplier of plastic film to manufacturers of magnetic recording media
(tape and discs) because the company was not in Japan then. 'We missed out
on the Japanese electronic media revolution of the 1980s,' says Richard
Sykes, the ICI Japan director responsible for the Melinex project.
The relative weakness and fragmentation of Japan's indigenous chemical
industry makes it easier for foreign chemical groups to expand there. The
largest Japanese chemical companies, Mitsubishi Kasei and Asahi Chemical,
are only one third the size of ICI, and chemicals are one of the few
manufacturing sectors in which Japan runs a trade deficit. Although a few
important chemical innovations have come out of Japan, the industry's
scientific and technological base is generally weak by western standards.
One important reason for this is that the Ministry of International Trade
and Industry (MITI), which has done so much behind the scenes to help other
industries organise their assault on world markets while protecting their
home base, does not take such an active interest in chemicals. 'At the end
of the day MITI is going to favour the automotive and electronics industries
rather than the chemical industry,' says Masinori Kato, ICI's Osaka branch
manager.
Even so, no foreign company ever finds it easy to establish itself in Japan.
In a country of full employment, where social attitudes still favour working
for a Japanese employer, staff recruitment can be extremely difficult. A
company expanding into Japan from abroad cannot rely solely on the
traditional recruitment policy of taking on university graduates who will
stay with it for life.
ICI has persuaded senior people to move to it in mid-career, by offering a
combination of higher salary, more time off work and a more interesting or
responsible job.
To help recruitment, particularly of new graduates, ICI has successfully
trod the path many foreign companies have followed of taking on 'senior
advisers' who have retired recently as managers of well-known Japanese
companies. 'One of their most important roles is to bring us contacts with
university professors who then refer their good students to ICI,' says John
Wilson, a New Zealander who runs ICI Japan's agrochemicals division.
'Personal recommendations by good university professors are the best source
of the best graduates.'
The highest ranking adviser is Shoichi Saba, former chairman of Toshiba, the
electronics giant, who served on ICI's main board as a non-executive
director from 1985 until February. Saba, now aged 72, is still a powerful
voice in Japanese government and business circles as vice-chairman of the
Keidanren (Federation of Economic Organisations), and he has done more than
any other individual to raise ICI's corporate profile in Japan.
On a personal level, Saba persuaded his former colleague Mikio Kurashima,
who had been head of Toshiba America, to join ICI Japan as executive
director responsible for personnel, planning, business development and
public relations. (John Russell, president of ICI Japan, heads a team of six
directors: three expatriate Britons and three Japanese.)
Kurashima says that, of all the differences between working for Toshiba and
ICI, language is the biggest. 'To put it simply: in Toshiba they work in
Japanese, in ICI they work in English. Japanese employees of ICI do talk in
Japanese when they're by themselves, but if there's a single Englishman
present - as there normally will be in a large meeting - the meeting will
have to take place in English.'
Looking at the language gap from the English side, Jim Armstrong, head of
ICI Pharmaceuticals in Japan, says: 'There are two languages you have to
learn in Japan: Japanese and Japanese English. It's surprising how often the
Japanese staff do not really understand the messages of letters arriving
here (from the UK). There's a whole series of English words that have a
particular meaning to the Japanese, which is different from the common
English usage.'
Apart from personnel and recruitment problems, western companies find it
more difficult than they would at home to get permission to build a factory
or research centre. In a densely populated country where land and labour are
very scarce, the prospect of creating jobs is no incentive for allowing
industrial development.
ICI executives have devoted a lot of time and effort to cultivating local
government officials in Ibaraki prefecture, north-east of Tokyo, where the
company has built the Melinex film plant, Japan Technical Centre and
Agricultural Research Station.
The pattern of land ownership in Japan is another complicating factor.
Although the Agricultural Research Station covers only eight hectares, ICI
had to negotiate with 38 separate landowners to buy the patchwork of paddy
fields it needed.
To help managers cultivate business contacts, ICI Japan has corporate
membership in three golf clubs. 'This pays off in terms of establishing
human relationships,' says John Wilson. 'Golf is not seen as competitive in
Japan but an enjoyable day out.'
Foreign businesses in Japan need to build up a relationship not only with
customers but also with suppliers. Given the strength of the Japanese
machine tool and electronics industries, it is surprising at first sight
that ICI imported two-thirds of the equipment for the new Melinex plant from
Germany, including the Siemens computerised control system. 'We originally
hoped to use more Japanese equipment but we discovered that to buy from the
Japanese we needed a longer-term relationship,' says a British engineer on
the Melinex project.
As polyester film begins to roll off the Melinex production lines, ICI's
Japanese staff are already lobbying hard for the group to allocate
substantial new funds to keep up the momentum of investment in Japan during
the 1990s. For example Toshiaki Harada, a manager in the Japan Technical
Centre, says: 'We think ICI's paints division should come to Japan.' He
argues that the future of its automotive paints business depends on building
a relationship with the Japanese car manufacturers.
But the next large-scale investment is most likely to be in
chlorofluoro-carbon substitutes. Japanese refrigerator and air conditioner
manufacturers will be extremely important customers for the Klea 134a, a
replacement for ozone-destroying CFC refrigerants. Scientists and engineers
at the Technical Centre are already working with Japanese customers on this;
a Klea factory in Japan would cost at least Pounds 75m and would open in the
mid-1990s.
With ICI cutting capital expenditure, however, in response to the current
downturn in the chemical industry, Sir Denys Henderson, the chairman, says
the board could not sanction a Klea plant for Japan until the US plant
(under construction) and in the UK have proved themselves.
Even so, Henderson emphasises that Japan - and the whole Asia Pacific region
 -will continue to receive high priority for investment. The medium-term
target is to double ICI's sales in Japan from Pounds 500m last year to
Pounds 1bn in 1995.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
