<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Technology: Barriers to British innovation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British companies are prevented from getting innovative products to market
due to a lack of skilled managers, a lack of knowledge of the marketplace
and an ignorance of what the customer wants, according to a new study by
consultants Arthur D Little.
The Product Innovation Survey paints a stark picture of Britain's innovative
capacity. The greatest concern for companies, the study reports, is getting
a new product to market on time - 80 per cent of respondents said this was
of concern.
By comparison only 40 per cent said that reducing the costs of developing
new products was a priority. And only 56 per cent said that improving the
appeal of new products was an area where they were applying more effort.
Conducted as part of a worldwide research project on product innovation,
which will be available in about two months, the Arthur D Little survey
questioned 70 of Britain's most innovative organisations. Most were
manufacturers and about 90 per cent of them had turnovers of more than
Pounds 100m.
The questionnaires were completed by the chief executive or the technical
director of the company, which, says Peter Scott-Morgan, associate director
of Arthur D Little, is one positive indicator from the survey. 'There is a
growing belief that the way you cope is through innovation,' he says.
More negative were the measures used by companies to assess whether they
were meeting their product development objectives. Some 86 per cent said
sales volumes were important while 83 per cent rated profitability. Product
quality only scored 48 per cent on the product development objective scale.
But perhaps the most telling indicator was when the companies were given a
list of 32 potential obstacles to innovation. Those that hindered innovation
most were the lack of skilled managers and lack of knowledge about the
marketplace, customers' and rivals.
</TEXT>
