<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Technology (Worth Watching): Progress in the diabetes fight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAELI researchers, in experiments on mice, have isolated a peptide which
can prevent the onset of diabetes and which might provide the basis for an
early diagnostic test and vaccine against the illness in humans.
In auto - immune diseases the immune system's 'T' cells, which are supposed
to fight disease, attack the body's own cells when they recognise a
particular peptide (a segment of protein). In the case of diabetes these are
the insulin-producing cells of the pancreas.
Researchers at the Weizmann Institute, in Rehovot, have found that by
isolating the appropriate peptide, and by giving extra doses of it to the
mice, the autoimmune attack could be aborted. The peptide is synthesised
from a protein which is present in human beings.
Weizmann Institute: Israel, 08 343512.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
