<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Technology (Worth Watching): Clothes that can sense the mood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DELLA BRADSHAW
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLOTHES which can change colour according to your mood is the promise of a
liquid crystal display technology developed in Poole, UK, by a division of
the German chemicals company Merck, of Darmstadt.
The technique uses liquid crystal ink, originally developed for use in
equipment such as thermometers, which is sensitive to heat and changes
colour as the temperature rises - from black to red, yellow, green, blue and
violet. It achieves this because the heat changes the viscosity of the
liquid crystal ink, and so the light reflected.
The task for Merck, which worked on the technology with Hull University and
the Royal Signals and Radar Establishment at Malvern, has been to develop an
ink which can be applied to textiles and survive washing or cleaning. This
has been achieved by combining the inks with a type of gelatin. A special
screen varnish can also be applied over the top.
Merck: Germany: 6151 720; UK, 0202 745520.
</TEXT>
