<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Technology: Rewards of friendship - Why AT&amp;T and NEC are
joining forces to produce the next generation of semiconductors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When AT&amp;T Microelectronics and NEC, the Japanese electronics company, were
calculating the potential savings to be made in jointly developing
technology to make future generations of semiconductors, they had to allow
for one extra cost - translation services.
The two companies have just agreed to develop a process for further
semiconductor miniaturisation, thus increasing the memory capacity and
functions of an individual chip, though the success of the project will
depend as much on human relations as on the sophistication of their
respective technologies.
Apart from saving money in the expensive race to develop ever more
sophisticated chips, the agreement reflects the emphasis placed by Japanese
electronics companies on cultivating strategic relationships with foreign
companies.
Close ties with AT&amp;T could bring NEC benefits not only in semiconductors, a
constant source of trade friction with the US, but also in the
telecommunications market, where trade disputes are also a problem.
The companies' announcement last week flowed from an agreement last year on
the development of application-specific integrated circuits (Asics) and came
a few days after the finalisation of a pact between Toshiba and the General
Electric Company of the US. Those two companies have agreed on the marketing
of humble home appliances and, more importantly, to launch research projects
in refrigeration technology, electronic controls and environment-related
technologies.
Chip partnerships have become commonplace between US and Japanese companies,
despite the ongoing disputes over access to the Japanese market. There are
tie-ups between NMB Semiconductor and Intel, Toshiba and Motorola, Sony and
Advanced Micro Devices, Matsushita and Intel, and Hitachi and Texas
Instruments (TI).
In February, Hitachi and TI announced that their 1988 pact had produced a
protective package for a 16Mbit dynamic random access memory (D-Ram) chip.
Their relationship is for the most part an exchange of information, which a
TI official in Japan said is 'working well', while the AT&amp;T and NEC
agreement is far more ambitious, involving exchanges of researchers and
joint funding of a project with broad applications.
Electronics companies are competing to cram increasing amounts of memory and
functions on to chips, meaning that they have to find ways to shrink the
circuits. Companies are now swinging into mass production of 4Mbit D-Ram
chips, and have begun to deliver samples of 16Mbit chips, but will need to
improve significantly manufacturing processes to market 64Mbit chips
successfully.
The development of 16Mbit chips is proceeding with 0.5-micron technology,
enabling circuits to be produced with a width of 0.5-microns (a micron is a
millionth of a metre). AT&amp;T and NEC have agreed to develop a 0.35-micron
process, which is regarded as essential for the mass production of future
chip generations.
Officials at AT&amp;T say the company presently has a 0.9-micron capability and
the tie-up with NEC will allow a matching of the company's strengths in
basic research with the chip technology skills of NEC, which has been the
leading Japanese producer.
Japanese companies complain that the costs of keeping ahead in the memory
race are multiplying faster than chip capacities, and the pressure of
competition is forcing the introduction of chips such as the 16Mbit D-Ram
even before the 4Mbit market has matured.
William Warwick, president of AT&amp;T Microelectronics, said that developing
the 0.35-micron process is likely to cost between Dollars 400m and Dollars
500m: 'I don't think that the agreement will save us half of those costs,
but it will be more than a quarter.'
The benefits of the partnership, he said, would be to 'share resources,
lower individual company risks, and gain timely access to technology'.
Tomihiro Matsumura, NEC's executive vice-president, said that the agreement
'represents true co-operation between two multinational semiconductor
companies'.
Precise details of that co-operation are yet to be finalised, but the
companies have agreed to divide the development process into 'modules', with
scientists at NEC and AT&amp;T working on agreed technology problems in their
respective laboratories in Japan and the US.
It is expected that there will be from 25 to 29 modules, and each company
will send a researcher to the other to monitor each module and ensure that
appropriate information is exchanged during the two-year programme. AT&amp;T and
NEC have agreed to report regularly on progress, and say that they are clear
in their own minds about the status of ownership rights - if a patent
follows joint work it will be jointly owned.
Research work will be conducted by the development division of AT&amp;T Bell
Laboratories and the chip development department of NEC, and will focus on
areas such as memory cell technology, ultra-fine circuiting technology and
ultra-fine etching technology.
If the project is successful, the two companies will have a common
0.35-micron technology and will be able to develop related products and,
perhaps, to share production lines to increase their manufacturing
flexibility.
'Our combined efforts will assure our customers timely access to a
leading-edge process technology that will be used to design sophisticated
components that will enhance the value and performance of our customers' end
systems,' Warwick suggested.
The sensitivity of the US-Japan relationship in electronics prompted AT&amp;T to
emphasise that the NEC partnership will not comprise the US company's
commitment to Sematech - the Texas-based US government-industry project
which had planned to develop 0.35-micron technology by 1993, but has fallen
behind schedule.
'AT&amp;T has supported Sematech since its inception and remains committed to
the efforts taking place at Sematech to assist the US semiconductor
industry,' Warwick said.
Steve Myers, senior industrial electronics analyst at Jardine Fleming, said
that the success of the joint research project will depend on
middle-management's interpretation of the aims of the executives who signed
the agreement.
'It requires very sophisticated management direction. The middle-level has
to understand exactly what they are supposed to be doing,' Myers said.
He said the agreement was useful for NEC, which has found the financial
commitments of advanced research a difficult burden, and would assist AT&amp;T,
which he said has not fulfilled its potential in chip marketing.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14 Illustration (Omitted).
