<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Management: Inadequate today, disastrous tomorrow -
Organisational structures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER LORENZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Since Peter Drucker let fly three years ago with a much-quoted article on
The Coming of the New Organisation, managers have been subjected to a
growing barrage of warnings from gurus and consultants that their
organisations will have to change character dramatically if they are to
survive far beyond the turn of the century.
At present, the argument runs, most organisations respond ineffectively to
today's competitive pressures because they are too hierarchical, too costly,
too slow to adapt, too unresponsive to customers, too demotivating to
employees, and altogether too limited in creativity and initiative. What is
merely inadequate today will become downright disastrous tomorrow.
To Drucker, Tom Peters, Charles Handy, and others, the ideal organisations
of the near future will be flat, flexible, and 'knowledge-based' - peopled
heavily by skilled professionals, in the widest sense.
Hence their citation of unlikely-looking models: Drucker favours orchestras
and hospitals (presumably the American, rather than the British variety),
while Peters and Handy tend to go for fast-moving TV stations such as CNN,
together with a handful of well-run management consultancies and other
professional service firms. To people who work in them, such organisations
may seem chaotic, but many do achieve their corporate objectives very
effectively.
Though a growing body of managers in all sorts of com panies and industries
does perceive the need for change, many executives find such examples either
daunting or unconvincing. So they will take heart from the claim that they
can, after all, discover the organisation of the future closer to home: in
the factories and financial operations departments of apparently
conventional organisations.
Writing in the latest issue of the McKinsey Quarterly, Steve Dichter, the
leader of the consultancy's organisation performance practice, argues that
radically new organisational principles are needed now.
He cites as a model a US General Electric factory making electrical circuit
breakers which now has only three levels of employee: 'associate' (shop
floor), advisor, and plant manager. The 'associates' are organised into
self-managing teams which perform traditional staff functions, such as
planning, capital investment requests, and recruitment. Elected facilitators
lead problem-solving teams, and cross-functional committees of 'associates'
meet weekly to deal with policy issues. Instant plant performance data is
available.
Since the early 1980s, over 400 units across a wide range of industries in
the US have been converted to this sort of approach; and the approach has
started to appear in Europe, reports Dichter.
Drawing on these examples, he promulgates a common set of characteristics
for what he calls, 'the organisation of the 1990s'. More akin to some of the
basic tenets of total quality management than he admits, they all contradict
sharply the 'command control' principles which have dominated western
corporate organisation since the early 1900s.
Hierarchy
To managers worried that such characteristics will not only undermine their
control, but diminish individual accountability and remove all hierarchy,
Dichter has a message designed to reassure: that a new, more effective type
of 'committed' control is created; that team and individual accountability
are enhanced; and that 'hierarchy remains as a very important dimension of
every organisation . . . they will continue to have a series of management
layers'.
The nine actions which Dichter says should be taken in order to create such
organisations are rather pedestrian compared with much of the other
available literature on the management of change.
More questionable, however, is whether, as Dichter claims, his ideal
organisation fully matches up to his criteria of being 'borderless,
networked, inverted, empowered, and non-hierarchical'. If not, then the
well-managed 'professional service' organisation may be a more sustainable,
if less comfortable, model after all.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 14
</PAGE>
</DOC>
