<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / TV transmission network will be sold by tender
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is to become the first country to privatise part of its television
transmission network, with the sale by tender of National
Transcommunications Ltd, formerly the Independent Broadcasting Authority's
engineering division.
City analysts believe the sale of NTL, which this year expects to make
pre-tax profit of about Pounds 9m on sales of Pounds 77m, may raise between
Pounds 150m and Pounds 200m.
NTL is expected to become one of the first new entrants into the UK's
liberalised telecommunications market. It is already in detailed
negotiations with the Office of Telecommunications, the industry regulator,
over a licence to use its network to transmit television, data and telephone
services.
It is thought likely that NTL might form alliances with groups such as cable
television operators seeking to take advantage of the government's recent
decision to end the telecommunications duopoly held by BT and Mercury.
Mr Peter Lloyd, the broadcasting minister, said bidders were expected to
include foreign telecommunications and television groups. The privatisation
is due in 1996.
Price Waterhouse, the government's lead financial adviser on the sale, said
it had already received inquiries from between 30 and 40 foreign and UK
companies.
The company operates about 475 transmitting sites and has access to a
further 475 run by the BBC.
NTL's main business is transmitting for the ITV independent television
companies, Channel 4, the Welsh fourth channel S4C, and 50 independent local
radio stations. This will this year generate Pounds 61m, of NTL's revenues.
Dr John Forrest, the company's executive chairman, forecast that within the
next few years a third of NTL's income might come from new business
activities, transmitting for television's planned Channel 5 and local
independent radio contractors, as well as video conferencing, data
transmission and telephony services to businesses.
NTL's management favours a bid from a consortium that would include a 15 per
cent stake for the company's 770 employees as well as bringing it access to
European markets.
Television South West, the ITV contractor for the west country, is backing
the Channel Three Wales and the West consortium, bidding for the commercial
television franchise held by HTV covering Wales and the west. TSW is joined
in the consortium by a number of institutional investors.
</TEXT>
