FT  03 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lords reject random breath tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PARLIAMENTARY campaign in favour of random breath testing to help cut
down on drink-driving suffered a setback yesterday when the House of Lords
rejected an amendment which would have introduced the new arrangements,
Alison Smith writes.
Instead, in a debate on the first day of the committee stage of the road
traffic bill, a majority of peers supported the government and voted against
the change by 87 to 41, a margin of 46.
The government has consistently said that the problem can be adequately
dealt with through the combination of the existing powers of the police both
to stop drivers for a wide range of motoring offences, and to administer
breath tests where they had reason to believe the driver was under the
influence of alcohol.
The change was proposed by Lord Clinton-Davis, an opposition transport
spokesman, who argued that it would provide an additional, effective
deterrent to drink-driving offences.
