<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Council Elections: Quest for clues to general election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRATEGISTS from the main political parties were preparing early today for a
deep analysis of the results of yesterday's local council elections to
assess the prospects for an early general election.
Polling in 369 local authorities in all parts of the country apart from
Scotland, Northern Ireland and greater London provided the most important
test of the post-Thatcher Tory party and the last big test before a decision
on election timing must be made.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, together with Mr Chris Patten,
Conservative party chairman and his advisers, will be examining the results
to see whether June remains an option or whether a date in the autumn or
next year is now inevitable.
Apart from Mr Major's own standing, the polls were regarded as a crucial
test for the proposed council tax. Ministers were anxious to discover
whether the plan for a property-based local tax had received general
approval and had therefore managed to kill local government finance as an
issue damaging to the government's electoral prospects.
Party analysts were particularly keen to study results from three areas  -
the north-west, the west and the east Midlands - where the next election
might be won or lost. Each area has a high proportion of Tory-held
marginals.
Among the councils that Labour had to capture if it is to have any chance of
winning the next election were Nottingham City, where the two main parties
were level-pegging, with the balance of power held by a Green party member;
West Lancashire District, where the Tories were defending a majority of one;
and Derby City, where the Conservatives were also battling to retain power.
At Gravesham Borough Council in Kent, often regarded as a seat that tends to
reflect the parties' national standing, Conservatives and Labour were
neck-and-neck, with the casting vote in the hands of the Conservative mayor.
Although most of the 28,500 candidates contesting the 12,255 seats at stake
accepted that many voters regarded the elections as a dry run for a general
election, local issues may have proved decisive in many areas.
The Liberal Democrats, more than any other party, have concentrated their
resources on local issues and were hoping to repeat the previous pattern of
doing much better in local elections than their national opinion poll
standing would suggest.
Gateway to the future: votes cast in Park ward in Nottingham may help to
decide the date of the general election
Decision-making process: a vote goes into the box
People power: a voter leaves the polling station
Voters make a mark in Woking in Surrey: the poll tax crisis in the UK has
prompted new interest in local politics
</TEXT>
