<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / World Trade News: Algeria and Italy in Dollars 7bn loan deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY and Algeria yesterday signed a package of loans worth Dollars 7bn.
This package is in the context of Italy's decision virtually to double the
amount of natural gas it will buy from Algeria over the next five years.
In addition, the loans are meant as a gesture towards north Africa's largest
country which is engaged in bold reforms aimed at liberalising its political
and economic system. They contrast sharply with the more reserved attitude
of Algeria's main trading partner, France.
The deal will help Algeria's Central Bank which has been sparing no effort
to lengthen the average maturity of the country's Dollars 25.3bn foreign
debt which had declined to just over three years by 1990, thus pushing up
the debt service ratio as a percentage of foreign debt to about 75 per cent.
A first tranche of Dollars 2.5bn is earmarked for the refinancing of credits
over the next seven years. Many of these are guaranteed by the Italian state
and fall due between January 1991 and January 1993.
The remaining Dollars 4.5bn, which will have to be raised through banks,
will be spent on the purchase of Italian goods and services.
</TEXT>
