<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Armenia questions Kremlin's integrity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ACCUSATIONS mounted yesterday that the Kremlin might be seeking to rekindle
the long-running land dispute between Armenia and Azerbaijan to serve its
own political interests.
Armenians say 36 people died on Tuesday when Soviet interior ministry troops
stormed two Armenian-populated villages north of the disputed enclave of
Nagorno-Karabakh, which is inside Azerbaijan but which Armenia lays claims
to.
The official aim of the operation was to crush Armenian guerrillas operating
in and outside the enclave.
Mr Levon Ter-Petrosian, the Armenian president, said yesterday the violence
appeared to have subsided after a promise by Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev on Tuesday to bring the situation under control.
But he told the Reuters news agency that he had evidence the attack was
designed to hinder Armenia's drive for independence and shore up Mr Ayaz
Mutalibov, Azerbaijan's Communist president.
Mr David Vardanyan, a senior Armenian parliamentary leader, told journalists
in Moscow that he believed Soviet military action was a reward by the
Kremlin for Azerbaijan's decision last week to sign the union treaty.
The renewed trouble also follows Armenia's controversial decision last week
to confiscate all Communist party property on its territory. President
Gorbachev has issued a decree overruling that move.
Significantly, a spokesman for Azerbaijan's Foreign Ministry voiced
suspicion over why trouble had started after three months of relative calm,
even though he denied Azerbaijan was to blame.
'It's in somebody's greater political interest that this should start again
now,' he said.
The two southern republics' conflict over Nagorno-Karabakh has cost hundreds
of lives over the past two years. It led last January to the Soviet army
declaring a state of emergency in Baku, the Azerbaijan capital, which is
still in force.
Since coming to power last summer, Mr Ter-Petrosian has succeeded in
disarming illegal Armenian militias, leading to a decline in clashes in
recent months. He warned yesterday, however, that any attempt to deport
Armenian militants from inside Azerbaijan could trigger violence beyond his
control.
</TEXT>
