<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Moscow clings on to east European reins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STUDENTS from Prague's College of Art were told recently that they could not
remove an old Soviet tank from the capital's fifth district.
So they decided to paint it a different colour. Pink.
Soviet diplomats were furious. There were protests, discussions, and
apologies all round. The tank, marking the liberation of Czechoslovakia by
the Red Army in 1945, was restored to its former colour. Khaki.
The fuss by Soviet officials exemplifies the deep sensitivities which today
characterise relations between the Soviet Union and its former east European
allies.
The Soviet military, and the older Soviet generation, resent what they see
as the growing ingratitude of the east Europeans for the way in which the
Red Army 'liberated' these countries from Hitler's Wehrmacht. They and
Communist party hardliners are also beginning to feel that the demise of the
Warsaw Pact and the cold war exposes the vulnerability of the Soviet Union's
own security.
This vulnerability forms the background to negotiations taking place on a
bilateral level between Moscow and the east European states. The Soviet
Union, and all the east European countries, want to place their relations on
a new and equal footing through friendship treaties.
As Mr David Meiszter, head of the Hungarian delegation to the talks with
Moscow, explained: 'The agreement should reflect a new quality of
partnership between Hungary and the Soviet Union, and comply with the
interests of both parties and the new European realities.'
But the Soviets have gone one stage further in interpreting the content of
the treaties, insisting that they should include a clause which states that
neither country will participate in any alliance directed against each
other.
This clause is already contained in the 'Treaty on co-operation,
good-neighbourliness and friendship' signed on March 22, between the Soviet
Union and Romania, the only country so far to have signed a treaty.
This pact also states that 'the two countries pledge not to tolerate the use
of their territories by a third state to commit an act of aggression against
the other side, and not to support such a state.'
Poland, Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Bulgaria, all of which aspire to
eventual membership of the European Community, staunchly oppose the
inclusion of this clause into any treaty.
Mr Tamas Katona, state secretary at the Hungarian Foreign Ministry, said
last week that 'the Soviet Union would like to achieve the creation of a
neutral region in eastern Europe similar to Finland.'
Mr Meiszter explained further that 'any clause which limits the scope of
action of Hungarian foreign policy is unacceptable.'
A Czechoslovak Foreign Ministry official said yesterday: 'There is a
stalemate in the negotiations between Prague and Moscow. From the
psychological perspective, somehow the Soviet military believes that we (the
countries of eastern Europe) are still within their sphere of influence;
that it is their right. They do not realise this is no longer the case.'
Polish diplomats are keen to stress the realpolitik of any agreement. 'There
is the question of geography - the size of Poland, where we are situated in
Europe. But they want us to state that we will not aspire to any alliance,'
commented a Polish diplomat.
'Our foreign minister, (Mr Krzysztof Skubiszewski) has always been cautious
about Poland aspiring to membership of any other alliance.'
However, over the past year several east European leaders, including
President Lech Walesa of Poland, have visited Nato headquarters to discover
what role the alliance (and maybe their own countries) will play in the new
Europe.
The Soviet Union may be persuaded to back down on the disputed clause
because it does not want to see the rest of the treaty jeopardised.
Whatever the outcome of the discussion, east European diplomats believe it
has highlighted the need for rethinking the whole of Europe's future
security arrangements.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6 Map (Omitted).
