<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Single Europe idea gathers strength
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST people in the European Community think that by the end of the century
they will be able to work anywhere in an enlarged EC, be paid in a single
currency and defended by a common EC military force.
This majority feeling that Community integration is inevitable, as well as
generally desirable, emerges from the latest Eurobarometer opinion poll,
sponsored by the Commission and published yesterday.
Out of some 13,000 people interviewed in March, 55 per cent said they
thought it was realistic to expect east European countries in the EC by the
year 2000. The ratio rose to 63 per cent in the case of neutral European
countries joining. Some 64 per cent expected a single currency, while 58 per
cent thought a common military force was realistic.
The wish, however, is father to the thought. In Denmark, 91 per cent
believed the accession to the EC by fellow Scandinavians was imminent, but
only 45 per cent of immigration-sensitive Danes considered free residence
rights were on the cards.
The one, predictable, drop in Euro-enthusiasm was detected in east Germany,
where the ratio of those giving the EC a positive endorsement dropped to 79
per cent, from 87 per cent last autumn.
</TEXT>
