<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Turks face tough choices in crusade against inflation and
debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TURKISH economic policy is in growing disarray, with the government and the
state bureaucracy increasingly deadlocked over how to tackle the twin
problems of inflation and public debt.
Ministers are being criticised by central bank and Treasury officials
concerned by the government's reluctance to curb spending as the country
prepares for general elections, which must be held before 1992.
Mr Rusdu Saracoglu, the central bank governor, a pivotal figure in Turkey's
economic recovery in the 1980s, believes that without a commitment to fiscal
restraint the bank cannot announce its 1991 monetary programme.
'The system is under great pressure. In our country short-term advances
drawn from the central bank are being used to bridge the budget deficit.
This is wrong,' he says.
Fiscal policy has long been Turkey's most pressing problem, aggravated by
the narrowness of Turkish capital markets and government concern to contain
foreign borrowing. In March the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and
Development (OECD) warned there was now a great temptation to resort to
'money creation which would have serious inflationary consequences'.
Central bank lending to the Treasury - in effect printing money to cover the
budget - has already exceeded the TL3,500bn (Pounds 530m) ceiling for
short-term low interest borrowing, agreed last year.
Mr Saracoglu complains that liquidity ratios, which require banks to hold 30
per cent of deposits in Treasury bills, are now being ignored by many
institutions. As a result the Treasury is forced increasingly to use central
bank credits for budget finance.
In this sort of climate it will be hard to rescue the central bank's
programme, which by keeping the growth of its own balance sheet below
nominal GNP was largely responsible for containing inflation in 1990 to
about 50 per cent.
'No central bank in the world can solve inflation if the government has such
a big budget deficit,' an Istanbul banker says.
Turkish employers enter annual pay talks with the unions later this month.
Before that the Soils Products Office has to announce 1991 support prices
for grains and other crops.
Meanwhile, in Paris in early June, Turkey has to give its annual account of
its economy to the OECD.
Given such a timetable the economic choices look even more daunting.
Mr Mahfi Egilmez, Treasury assistant under-secretary, warns: 'It is too late
for short-term ad hoc measures.'
The official target for the fiscal deficit was set at 7.5 per cent of GNP.
Mr Egilmez says that the central government's deficit alone - which excludes
state enterprises - could reach TL30,000bn, compared with the TL20,000bn
target.
The central bank is calling for a new medium-term austerity programme to
control public finances. 'Selling the programme, articulating the policy and
convincing the public at large is now essential,' says Mr Saracoglu.
Last week President Turgut Ozal warned the unions their current demands
could set the country back 10 years. Mr Isin Celebi, the economics minister,
announced he would end support for tobacco and grain prices.
Though politically difficult, cutting farm subsidies is clearly one
immediate option, together with a freeze on civil servants' salaries and a
new pricing policy to reduce losses of state enterprises.
The politicians' concern is that more far-reaching cuts could damage the
electoral chances of the ruling Motherland party (ANAP).
Mr Celebi predicts nothing will be decided until after ANAP delegates meet
in June, when liberals in the party are expected to challenge Mr Yildirim
Akbulut, the prime minister, for the party leadership.
However, bankers and foreign economists are worried that without a fuller
cabinet shake-up, any new programme will have little credibility.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-1799</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BECBBAANFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910503
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 MAY 91 / Brussels stands by to repel boarders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community should be tougher towards foreigners wanting to enter
the EC, but tenderer to immigrants already settled there, according to a
Brussels document for discussion by foreign ministers later this month.
The paper, which the Commission is expected to approve formally next week,
talks of a rising tide of immigration from the Mediterranean and eastern
Europe. But its recommendations hardly amount to the Fortress Europe policy
feared by human right groups.
'The question is no longer how to stop immigration, but rather to influence
it in a positive way,' it says.
Apart from suggesting that the 12 EC states should harmonise their controls
on illegal immigration and procedures for dealing with people 'shopping'
around the Community for asylum, the thrust of the Commission's external
policy recommendations is to increase the economic incentives for
neighbouring populations to stay put.
Aid from the EC budget and individual member states should be targeted at
providing work for those most likely to migrate to the EC - the illiterate
poor in the cities of the south, and the professionals who create a brain
drain from developing countries by moving to the EC. The association
agreements that are being re-negotiated with Mediterranean and east European
countries this year should deal specifically with migration policy.
On the internal front, the Commission suggests that immigrants who retain
third country nationality, but are legally established in the Community,
should no longer be denied the freedom to travel or the access to national
or EC social benefits that EC citizens have.
The Twelve are shortly expected to ratify a convention that will pave the
way for a common tourist visa for third country nationals. This will create
a ridiculous situation, said an EC official yesterday, in which 'an
Ethiopian visitor, for instance, will be able to swan around the Community
on one visa, whereas a longtime, legal Algerian resident of France will
continue to need a visa for each of the other 11 EC countries he might want
to visit'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
