<HEADLINE>
FT  02 MAY 91 / Parliament and Politics: Lilley to press ahead with sell-off
of ECGD division - Trade and Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PETER LILLEY, the trade and industry secretary, yesterday ignored Labour
demands for the abandonment of the sale of the Insurance Services Group of
the Export Credit Guarantee Department.
He insisted that privatisation of the concern would ensure that it was
'better in tune' with the European Community single market.
Leading the demands for the abandonment of the sale in the Commons Mr Gordon
Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary, quoted the view of the British
Exporters Association that it was turning into 'a shambles'.
He argued since there was no serious British bidder the organisation could
be controlled from Rome or Amsterdam.
Mr Brown maintained that the government's decision to pursue the sale was
privatisation 'for privatisation's sake'.
Mr Lilley emphasised that other EC countries, including Germany, the
Netherlands, France, Italy, Belgium, Portugal and Spain relied on the
private sector to provide export credit facilities. He said Denmark and
Ireland were also considering privatising their export agencies.
Mr Lilley told Mr Brown: 'For the same reasons we believe that export credit
for short term business should be in the private sector'.
Mr Tim Sainsbury, the trade minister, confirmed that the invitation to
tender had brought 'responses' from three companies  - Assicurazioni
Generali, NCM and Trade Indemnity.
He said: 'There will now be a period of evaluation by Government and its
advisers, with a view to proceeding as quickly as practicable with the sale
of the short term business, subject to the successful passage of the Export
and Investment Guarantee Bill.'
The financial robustness of the proposed purchaser, the price offered, and
commitment to and understanding of the business would be among the factors
taken into account.
Ms Joyce Quin, from the Labour front bench, described the proposed sale as a
'fiasco'.
She claimed that exporters were alarmed and dismayed at the prospect of the
organisation being privatised.
Mr Sainsbury replied that the CBI, amongst others, had welcomed the proposed
privatisation which would enable the the Insurance Services Group to provide
better and more flexible services to British industry.
Mr Edward Leigh, junior trade and industry minister, yesterday encouraged
the Post Office to seek ways of offering greater choice to its customers.
He said 'We are prepared to look at any proposal put forward by the Post
Office to improve the quality of services to the customer'.
Mr Leigh, an enthusiastic advocate of privatisation, denied that the steps
already taken by the Post Office to establish separate divisions for its
counter, mails and parcels services were intended as a prelude to
privatisation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
